(South)<br/> HR-87 (West)<br/> HR-38 (Commercial)<br/> DL-16 (Delhi NCR)\n| website                         = {{url|http://faridabad.nic.in}}<br/>{{url|http://mcfaridabad.org}}\n| official_name                   = \n| blank_info_sec1                 = {{nowrap|{{increase}} 0.696<ref name=\"unhdi-gdl\">{{cite web |title=Government of Haryana\u2013 District Database |url=https://in.one.un.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/SDG-Vision-Documnet-Haryana-Final.pdf \n }}</ref> ({{color|Orange| medium}})}} \n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] {{nobold|(2017)}}\n}}\n\n{{Maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-width=250|frame-height=280|zoom=6|frame-lat=29.185|frame-long=76.225\n|type=shape-inverse|id=Q1174|title=Haryana\n|type2=point|id2=Q200663|stroke-width=1|title2=Faridabad\n}}\n\n'''Faridabad''' is the [[List of cities in Haryana by population|most populous city]] in the Indian state of [[Haryana]]. It is a leading industrial centre and is situated in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]] bordering the Indian capital [[New Delhi]].<ref name=\"tribuneindia2005\"/> It is one of the major satellite cities of Delhi and is located 284 kilometres south of the state capital [[Chandigarh]]. The river [[Yamuna]] forms the eastern district boundary with Uttar Pradesh. The [[Government of India]] included it in the second list of [[Smart Cities Mission]] on 24 May 2016.<ref name=Smrt1>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lucknow-warangal-2nd-list-of-smart-cities-is-out-10-facts-1409414|title=Lucknow, Warangal...2nd List of Smart Cities Is Out: 10 Facts|access-date=24 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527075434/http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/lucknow-warangal-2nd-list-of-smart-cities-is-out-10-facts-1409414|archive-date=27 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Faridabad has been described as the eighth fastest growing city in the world and the third in [[India]] by the [[City Mayors Foundation]] survey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth1.html|title=City Mayors: World's fastest growing urban areas (1)|website=www.citymayors.com|access-date=18 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125090345/http://citymayors.com/statistics/urban_growth1.html|archive-date=25 November 2010|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As per the 2001 Delhi regional plan, Faridabad is part of the Delhi Metropolitan Area (DMA).<ref>{{cite web |title=Evaluation Study of DMA Towns in National Capital Region|url=http://tcpomud.gov.in/divisions/mutp/dma/final_dma_report.pdf|website=Town and Country Planning Organisation|publisher=[[Ministry of Urban Development]]|accessdate=19 March 2017|date=September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320052724/http://tcpomud.gov.in/divisions/mutp/dma/final_dma_report.pdf|archivedate=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe newly developed residential and industrial part of Faridabad (Sec. 66 to 89) between the [[Agra Canal]] and the Yamuna River is commonly referred as [[Greater faridabad|Greater Faridabad]]. The area is being developed as a self-sustained sub-city with wide roads, tall buildings, malls, educational institutions, and health and commercial centres. Sectors 66 to 74 are Industrial Sectors, while Sectors 75 to 89 are Residential Sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmespaces.com/news_detail.php?id=180|title=Acme Spaces|work=acmespaces.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124164712/http://www.acmespaces.com/news_detail.php?id=180|archive-date=24 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFaridabad is a major industrial hub of Haryana.<ref name=\"tribuneindia2005\"/> 50% of the income tax collected in Haryana is from Faridabad and Gurgaon.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Tribune|date=28 December 2005|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051228/delhi.htm|access-date=27 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613023249/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051228/delhi.htm|archive-date=13 June 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Faridabad is famous for [[henna]] production from the agricultural sector, while tractors, motorcycles, switch gears, refrigerators, shoes, tyres and garments constitute its primary industrial products.\n\nIn 2018, Faridabad was considered by the [[World Health Organization]] as the world's [[List of most polluted cities by particulate matter concentration|second most polluted city]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dasgupta |first=Neha |date=16 May 2018 |title=With world's worst air, Indian city struggles to track pollution |url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/worlds-worst-air-indian-city-struggles-track-pollution-132116286.html |work=Yahoo News |agency=Reuters |location=United States |access-date=16 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516183730/https://ca.news.yahoo.com/worlds-worst-air-indian-city-struggles-track-pollution-132116286.html |archive-date=16 May 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}<br/>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Indian city struggles with 'world's worst air' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video/world/indian-city-struggles-with-worlds-worst-air/2018/05/16/af6d973a-58f1-11e8-9889-07bcc1327f4b_video.html |work=Washington Post |location=United States |date=16 May 2018 |access-date=16 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704094424/https://www.washingtonpost.com/video/world/indian-city-struggles-with-worlds-worst-air/2018/05/16/af6d973a-58f1-11e8-9889-07bcc1327f4b_video.html |archive-date=4 July 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFaridabad has been selected as one of the hundred Indian cities to be developed as a [[smart city]] under [[Government of India]]'s flagship [[Smart Cities Mission]] by [[Ministry of Urban Development (India)|Ministry of Urban Development]].\n\n== History ==\n\nFaridabad was founded in 1607 by Shaikh Far\u012bd, the treasurer for the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] emperor [[Jahangir]], to protect the [[Grand Trunk Road]] between [[Delhi]] and [[Agra]]. It was constituted a municipality in 1867. A project for [[overseas Pakistani#Post independence|Pakistani refugee resettlement]] and light industrial development was initiated in the city in 1950.<ref name=BritannicaOnline>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]] |title=Faridabad |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Faridabad |access-date=2019-03-14 |publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.]] |location=Chicago, Illinois |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406015944/http://www.britannica.com/place/Faridabad |archive-date=6 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In Independent India, Faridabad was initially a part of [[Gurgaon district]] which was later made an independent district on 15 August 1979.\n\n== Geography ==\n=== Climate ===\n{{climate chart\n|Faridabad\n|8|21|15\n|10|23|19\n|15|30|21\n|21|36|27\n|26|39|29\n|28|39|61\n|27|35|214\n|26|34|228\n|25|34|100\n|19|33|21\n|13|28|5\n|8|22|14\n|units = metric|float = right|source = ''Weather 2''<ref name=\"Weather 2\">{{cite web|title=August Climate History for Faridabad|url=http://www.myweather2.com/City-Town/India/Faridabad/climate-profile.aspx|publisher=Weather 2|access-date=5 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921212026/http://www.myweather2.com/City-Town/India/Faridabad/climate-profile.aspx|archive-date=21 September 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>}}\n\nFaridabad has a borderline [[semi-arid climate#Hot semi-arid climates|hot semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''BSh'') just short of a dry-winter [[humid subtropical climate]] (''Cwa''). The city features the three typical Indian seasons - The \"hot\" or pre-monsoon season lasts from late March to late June and is typified by sweltering and arid conditions that begin very dry but latterly turn humid. The \"wet\" or [[Monsoon of South Asia|monsoon]] season is sweltering and often dangerously humid with frequent but erratic heavy rainfall. Following the retreat of the monsoon is the \"cool\" or winter season with warm and sunny weather producing by far the most comfortable conditions.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Faridabad\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n\n|Jan high C = 21\n|Feb high C = 23\n|Mar high C = 30\n|Apr high C = 36\n|May high C = 39\n|Jun high C = 39\n|Jul high C = 35\n|Aug high C = 34\n|Sep high C = 34\n|Oct high C = 33\n|Nov high C = 28\n|Dec high C = 22\n\n|Jan low C = 8\n|Feb low C = 10\n|Mar low C = 15\n|Apr low C = 21\n|May low C = 26\n|Jun low C = 28\n|Jul low C = 27\n|Aug low C = 26\n|Sep low C = 25\n|Oct low C = 19\n|Nov low C = 13\n|Dec low C = 8\n\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm = 15\n|Feb rain mm = 19\n|Mar rain mm = 21\n|Apr rain mm = 27\n|May rain mm = 27\n|Jun rain mm = 61\n|Jul rain mm = 214\n|Aug rain mm = 228\n|Sep rain mm = 100\n|Oct rain mm = 21\n|Nov rain mm = 5\n|Dec rain mm = 14\n|source = ''Weather 2''<ref name=\"Weather 2\"/>}}\n\n== Administration ==\nThe list is as below:<ref>{{citation|title=Administration|url=http://faridabad.nic.in/administration.htm|publisher=faridabad.nic.in|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150730083822/http://faridabad.nic.in/administration.htm|archive-date=30 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://faridabad.nic.in/whos-who/ |title=Who's Who &#124; District Faridabad, Government of Haryana &#124; India |access-date=1 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401140512/https://faridabad.nic.in/whos-who/ |archive-date=1 April 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! S. No. !! Department !! Title !! Position Holder !! Qualification\n|-\n| # || Administration|| Divisional Commissioner ||Sh. Sanjay Joon\t\n| IAS\n|-\n| 1 || Administration|| Deputy Commissioner & District Magistrate ||Sh. Yashpal Yadav\n| IAS\n|-\n| 2 || Administration || Additional Deputy Commissioner ||Sh. Ram Kumar Singh\n| IAS\n|-\n| 3 ||Municipal Corporation of Faridabad (MCF) || Commissioner || Sh. Yash Garg || IAS\n|-\n| 4 || Municipal Corporation of Faridabad (MCF) || Chief Engineer ||Sh. Raman Sharma\n| \n|-\n| 5 || Judiciary || District & Sessions Judge || Sh. Deepak Gupta || HCS (Judicial)\n|-\n| 6 || Police || Commissioner of Police|| Sh. Krishan Kumar Rao|| IPS\n|}\n\n.# Faridabad, Palwal and Nuh district jointly falls under '''Faridabad Division''' of [[Haryana]]. A Division is headed by a Divisional Commissioner.\n\nFaridabad has a good judiciary system with its headquarters at District Court in Sector 12 which came into existence on 8 December 1980 with Shri A.P. Chaudhary as first District & Sessions Judge, Faridabad. The District court has its [[Bar association]] with more than 2000 lawyers as its members<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://districts.ecourts.gov.in/faridabad|title=District Court Faridabad|last=Faridabad|first=District Court|date=3 October 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\nThe Faridabad Small Industries Association claims that Faridabad and Gurgaon districts account for almost 56% of the income tax collected in Haryana.<ref name=\"tribuneindia2005\">{{citation|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051228/delhi.htm#1|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India \u2013 Delhi and neighbourhood|access-date=27 May 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613023249/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20051228/delhi.htm#1|archive-date=13 June 2007|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Faridabad has been selected as one of the hundred Indian cities to be developed as a [[smart city]] under [[Narendra Modi|PM Narendra Modi's]] flagship [[Smart Cities Mission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/business/why-only-98-cities-instead-of-100-announced-all-questions-answered-about-smart-cities-project-2410576.html|title=Why only 98 cities instead of 100 announced: All questions answered about smart cities project|work=Firstpost|access-date=21 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119003746/http://www.firstpost.com/business/why-only-98-cities-instead-of-100-announced-all-questions-answered-about-smart-cities-project-2410576.html|archive-date=19 January 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Taxation===\nFaridabad's share in total VAT collection in the state was 17% in 2012\u201313. For the same period, Faridabad's contribution to Central Sales Tax was 15% and to Entertainment Tax was 13%.<ref>{{citation|last=Sharma|first=Sumedha|title='Smart' Faridabad seeks monetary help from Gurgaon|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/mobi/news/haryana/community/-smart-faridabad-seeks-monetary-help-from-gurgaon/147407.html|publisher=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]|date=18 October 2015|location=Gurgaon|agency=Tribune News Service}}</ref><ref name=gurgaon>{{citation|title=70% of Haryana's investment comes from Gurgaon, says industry body|url=http://hindustantimes.com/gurgaon/70-of-haryana-s-investment-comes-from-gurgaon-says-industry-body/story-hTHFEXrCvgeYg7QTR0J84M.html|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|date=9 October 2015|access-date=19 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011070437/http://www.hindustantimes.com/gurgaon/70-of-haryana-s-investment-comes-from-gurgaon-says-industry-body/story-hTHFEXrCvgeYg7QTR0J84M.html|archive-date=11 October 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Agriculture ===\n[[File:Banas Dairy Faridabad.jpg|thumb|right|[[Amul]] Banas Dairy]]\nFaridabad is the largest exporter of [[henna]] (Mehandi) in India. According to the Faridabad Henna Manufacturing Association, the sale of henna from Faridabad is worth an estimated {{INRConvert|250|c}}\u2013{{INRConvert|300|c}} annually.<ref>{{citation|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-03-19/news/31210756_1_lawsonia-inermis-exporters-dye|title=Faridabad's henna industry dying due to stiff competition from other countries and state policy \u2013 timesofindia-economictimes|access-date=1 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418232107/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-03-19/news/31210756_1_lawsonia-inermis-exporters-dye|archive-date=18 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Central government offices ===\n[[File:Npti at night.jpg|thumb|alt=NPTI Corporate Office, Faridabad|[[National Power Training Institute]] Corporate Office, Faridabad]]\n\nMany directorates of different union government ministries are headquartered in Faridabad including Central Ground Water Board, Department of Plant Quarantine and Central Insecticide Lab,<ref>{{citation|url=http://cgwb.gov.in/contact_us.html|title=Central Ground Water Board, Ministry of Water Resources, RD &GR Government of India|access-date=1 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903042026/http://www.cgwb.gov.in/contact_us.html|archive-date=3 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Union Government Offices from Haryana including the Commissioner of Central Excise within Department of Revenue, Government of India, Department of Explosives, and Department of Labour. Institute such as National Council for Cement and Building Materials, a research and development institute under the ministry of commerce, and industry has its head office in Faridabad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Isha |first1=Dewri |title=Haryana Ladli Yojana {{!}} What are the benefits of\u00a0Ladli Yojna in Haryana |url=https://sarkariduniya.com/en/haryana-ladli-yojana/ |access-date=28 November 2018 |agency=sarkariduniya |date=26 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128164704/https://sarkariduniya.com/en/haryana-ladli-yojana/ |archive-date=28 November 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Apex Central Training Institute of the Department of Revenue, Government of India, National Academy of Customs Excise & Narcotics is located at Sector 29. The [[National Power Training Institute]], an autonomous body under [[Ministry of Power (India)|Ministry of Power]], [[Government of India]] has a corporate office in Faridabad.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nptidelhi.net/ |title=HOME |publisher=Npti Delhi |date=2012-03-25 |access-date=2015-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108055124/http://www.nptidelhi.net/ |archive-date=8 November 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The city also hosts the National Institute of Financial Management, which serves as training academy for accounting and financial services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nifm.ac.in/Site/Index.aspx|title=National Institute of Financial Management|access-date=27 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304151422/http://www.nifm.ac.in/Site/Index.aspx|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:NHPC Corporate Office.jpg|thumb|NHPC Corporate Office, Faridabad]]\nAlso headquartered here is [[NHPC Limited]]\nwhich is a Central PSU under Ministry of Power, Government of India and the largest Hydro-power Company in India.\n\nAn office of Geological Survey of India is also located in NIT-5 area of the city.\n\n=== Industries ===\n[[File:Larsen & Toubro Office.png|thumb|[[Larsen & Toubro]] Office at Faridabad.]]\nFaridabad is the industrial capital of [[Haryana]].<ref name=\"tribuneindia2005\"/> As of 2013, out of total 11,665 registered working factories in Haryana, 2,499 were in Faridabad which was followed by Gurgaon with 2,116 factories. According to a study, the growth of Faridabad has been declining in the last 2 decades, the share of Faridabad in investment is less than 1% and 93% of investment is in the paper industry. The industrial contribution of Faridabad to [[Haryana]]'s revenue was declined from 29% to 22% in 2012\u201313.<ref name=gurgaon />\n\nFaridabad is home to large-scale companies like [[Escorts Group|Escorts Limited]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escortsgroup.com|title=Best Tractor Manufacturing Companies India, Top Tractor Companies in India, Most Selling Tractor in India- Escorts Group - Escorts Group|website=www.escortsgroup.com|access-date=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080712220444/http://www.escortsgroup.com/|archive-date=12 July 2008|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> India [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]] Motor Pvt. Ltd., [[Havells]] India Limited,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.havells.com/company-profile.aspx|title=File not found|access-date=18 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222095909/http://www.havells.com/company-profile.aspx|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[JCB (company)|JCB]] India Limited, [[Indian Oil]] (R&D),<ref>{{cite web|author=Manohar, Asit|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/news/31240306_1_bio-fuels-research-work-indian-oil-corporation|title=IOC Faridabad unit to pump in bio-fuel; R&D unit gearing to reduce pressure on conventional fuel|work=Times of India|date=26 March 2012|access-date=4 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208113631/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2012-03-26/news/31240306_1_bio-fuels-research-work-indian-oil-corporation|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Larsen & Toubro]] (L&T),<ref>[http://www.lntgulf.com/contact-us.html L&T-Gulf Private Limited<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041859/http://www.lntgulf.com/contact-us.html |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> [[Whirlpool Corporation|Whirlpool]] India Ltd., [[ABB Group]], [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] India Ltd., [[Bata Shoes|Bata]] India Ltd and [[Eicher tractor|Eicher]] Tractor Ltd. and Beebay Kidswear<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://faridabad.nic.in/fbdnew/industriallsi.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208115729/http://faridabad.nic.in/fbdnew/industriallsi.htm |archive-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Eyewear e-tailer [[Lenskart]] and healthcare startup [[Lybrate]] have their headquarters in Faridabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/eyewear-etailer-lenskart-looks-at-150-growth-this-fiscal/article7916307.ece|title=Eye-wear e-tailer Lenskart looks at 150% growth this fiscal|author=Abhishek Law|work=The Hindu Business Line|access-date=4 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211195817/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/eyewear-etailer-lenskart-looks-at-150-growth-this-fiscal/article7916307.ece|archive-date=11 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Faridabad-Rents-climbing-sleepy-town-is-hot-property/articleshow/47728780.cms|title=Faridabad: Rents climbing, sleepy town is hot property|work=The Times of India|access-date=4 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622054331/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Faridabad-Rents-climbing-sleepy-town-is-hot-property/articleshow/47728780.cms|archive-date=22 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> More than 5,000 units of auto parts producers are based in Faridabad.<ref name=\"Amarujala\">{{citation |title=\u092c\u093e\u0907\u0915 \u0938\u0947 \u0932\u0947\u0915\u0930 \u0939\u0935\u093e\u0908 \u091c\u0939\u093e\u091c \u0924\u0915 \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u0941\u0930\u094d\u091c\u0947 \u092c\u0928\u0924\u0947 \u092b\u0930\u0940\u0926\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926 \u092e\u0947\u0902 |url=http://www.amarujala.com/chandigarh/msme-haryana-faridabad-auto-parts-industry-story-hindi-news |work=[[Amar Ujala]] |access-date=29 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914165401/http://www.amarujala.com/chandigarh/msme-haryana-faridabad-auto-parts-industry-story-hindi-news |archive-date=14 September 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lakhani Armaan Group has set up manufacturing facilities at Faridabad (Haryana).{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n==Transportation and connectivity==\n\n===Rail===\nFaridabad is on the broad gauge of the New Delhi \u2013 Mumbai Line. New Delhi and Hazrat Nizammudin Railway Station is about 25&nbsp;km away from [[Faridabad railway station|Old Faridabad railway station]]. The trains for big cities like [[Mumbai]], [[Hyderabad]], [[Chennai]] are easily accessible from here. Local trains runs between [[New Delhi]] to Faridabad.<ref name=mcf>{{citation|title=Faridabad Connectivity|url=https://mcfbd.com/faridabad-connectivity|last=Municipal Corporation Faridabad|date=2015|access-date=9 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150809022629/http://mcfbd.com/faridabad-connectivity/|archive-date=9 August 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Metro===\n{{see also|Violet Line (Delhi Metro)}}\n[[File:DelhiMetroVioletLine.JPG|thumb|Delhi Metro Violet Line]]\n[[Delhi Metro]] [[Violet Line (Delhi Metro)|Violet Line]] connects Faridabad with Delhi. The extension of Violet Line to Faridabad was inaugurated by [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] on 6 Sepetmeber 2015.<ref>{{citation |title=PM Narendra Modi travels by Delhi Metro |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-09-06/news/66268172_1_pm-narendra-modi-delhi-metro-rail-corporation-faridabad |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=6 September 2015 |access-date=9 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925124930/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-09-06/news/66268172_1_pm-narendra-modi-delhi-metro-rail-corporation-faridabad |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> There are 9 metro stations in Faridabad corridor of Delhi Metro which are all elevated.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.delhimetrorail.com/press_reldetails.aspx?id=63aQSC8zmhslld |title=Faridabad Metro Corridor \u2013 Press Brief |work=Delhimetrorail.com |date=2015-09-25 |access-date=3 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101225813/http://www.delhimetrorail.com/press_reldetails.aspx?id=63aQSC8zmhslld |archive-date=1 January 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Metro has been recently elongated to Ballabhgarh with the addition of two stations- [[Sant Surdas (Sihi) metro station|Sant Surdas Sih]]i and [[Raja Nahar Singh metro station|Raja Nahar Singh]] Ballabhgarh.\n\nHaryana government is also planning to link Faridabad and Gurgaon by Metro.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/haryana/faridabad-gurgaon-metro-link-set-to-become-reality/18596.html |title=Faridabad-Gurgaon Metro link set to become reality |work=Tribuneindia.com |date=2014-12-16 |access-date=3 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208170518/http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/haryana/faridabad-gurgaon-metro-link-set-to-become-reality/18596.html |archive-date=8 December 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Currently the Faridabad corridor of Delhi Metro Violet Line is the longest metro corridor in the [[National Capital Region (India)|National Capital Region]] (NCR) consisting of 11 stations and the total length of corridor being 14&nbsp;km.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/newdelhi/ncr-s-longest-metro-line-in-faridabad/article1-800767.aspx |title=NCR's longest Metro line in Faridabad &#124; delhi |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=2012-01-23 }}</ref>\n\nThe 11 metro stations are [[Sarai metro station|Sarai]], [[NHPC Chowk metro station|NHPC Chowk]], [[Mewala Maharajpur metro station|Mewala Maharajpur]], [[Sector 28 metro station|Sector 28]], [[Badkhal Mor metro station|Badkhal Mor]], [[Old Faridabad metro station|Old Faridabad]], [[Neelam Chowk Ajronda metro station|Neelam Chowk Ajronda]], [[Bata Chowk metro station|Bata Chowk]], [[Escorts Mujesar metro station|Escorts Mujesar]], [[NCB Colony metro station|Sant Surdas (Sihi)]] and [[Ballabhgarh metro station|Raja Nahar Singh]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.delhimetrorail.com/press_reldetails.aspx?id=63aQSC8zmhslld |title=Faridabad Metro Corridor \u2013 Press Brief |work=delhimetrorail.com |access-date=3 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101225813/http://www.delhimetrorail.com/press_reldetails.aspx?id=63aQSC8zmhslld |archive-date=1 January 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Delhi Faridabad Skyway.png|thumb|A view of [[Delhi Faridabad Skyway]]]]\n\nFaridabad is well connected with [[Delhi]] through [[Delhi Faridabad Skyway]] (Badarpur Flyover).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/noida/Two-bridges-across-Yamuna-to-link-Noida-and-Haryana/articleshow/23362941.cms|title=Two bridges across Yamuna to link Noida and Haryana|work=The Times of India|access-date=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106152234/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/noida/Two-bridges-across-Yamuna-to-link-Noida-and-Haryana/articleshow/23362941.cms|archive-date=6 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Nod-for-road-joining-Greater-Noida-Faridabad/articleshow/40205603.cms|title=Nod for road joining Greater Noida, Faridabad|work=The Times of India|access-date=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106234220/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Nod-for-road-joining-Greater-Noida-Faridabad/articleshow/40205603.cms|archive-date=6 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation|last=Tiwary|first=A K|title=Connectivity, smooth traffic, REAL GROWTH! FNG Expressway will be a boon for daily commuters once it is complete; also, it is emerging as a growth corridor for real estate development.|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=CAP/2014/04/12&PageLabel=57&EntityId=Ar05700&ViewMode=HTML|access-date=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820040648/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=TOINEW&BaseHref=CAP%2F2014%2F04%2F12&PageLabel=57&EntityId=Ar05700&ViewMode=HTML|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kalindi-kunj-bypass-najeeb-jung-badarpur-vorder-dnd-noida-faridabad/1/357787.html|title=Kalindi Kunj bypass gets a go ahead at last|access-date=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509014007/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kalindi-kunj-bypass-najeeb-jung-badarpur-vorder-dnd-noida-faridabad/1/357787.html|archive-date=9 May 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>http://sofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/Lieutenant-governor-clears-Kalindi-Kunj-bypass/articleshow/26757418.cms{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Airways===\nFaridabad is served by [[Indira Gandhi International Airport]], New Delhi which is around 35&nbsp;km from Faridabad.<ref name=mcf /> The airport is one of the busiest airports in India and provides domestic and international air connectivity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newdelhiairport.in/fact-sheet.aspx|title=Indira Gandhi Delhi International Airport \u2013 Fact Sheet|work=newdelhiairport.in|access-date=12 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106213309/http://www.newdelhiairport.in/fact-sheet.aspx|archive-date=6 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAs per 2011 census, Faridabad had a population of 1,404,653 out of which males were 750,446 and females were 654,207.<ref name=\"2011 Census of India\">{{cite web | url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | title=Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011; Cities having population 1 lakh and above | publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India | access-date=10 October 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507135928/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | archive-date=7 May 2012 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The literacy rate was 83.04 per cent.<ref>{{citation|title=Census 2011 at a Glance (District Faridabad)|url=http://faridabad.nic.in/census2011.htm|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504100306/http://faridabad.nic.in/census2011.htm|archive-date=4 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of education facilities in Faridabad}}\n\n===Higher education===\nThere are numerous educational institutions in Faridabad that offer higher education courses. These colleges provide courses in different field like science, medicine, arts, commerce, engineering, MCA, etc. Some of the colleges that offer graduate and undergraduate courses include:{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n<!-- ONLY ADD AN INSTITUTION TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n* [[Institute of Hotel Management, Faridabad]]\n* [[Lingaya's University]]\n* [[Manav Rachna International University]]\n* [[National Power Training Institute]]\n* [[ESIC Medical College, Faridabad|ESIC Medical College]]\n* [[Regional Centre for Biotechnology]] (RCB)\n* [[Translational Health Science and Technology Institute]] (THSTI) \n* [[YMCA University of Science and Technology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Healthcare==\n[[File:Academic Block, ESIC Medical College and Hospital, Faridabad.jpg|thumb|[[ESIC Medical College, Faridabad]]]]\nThere are many private and government hospitals in Faridabad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hospitalkhoj.com/hospitals/private/faridabad|title=Private Hospital in Faridabad|work=hospitalkhoj.com|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124183058/http://www.hospitalkhoj.com/hospitals/private/faridabad|archive-date=24 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faridabadonline.in/city-guide/hospitals-in-faridabad|title=Hospitals in Faridabad|work=faridabadonline.in|access-date=8 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125070958/http://www.faridabadonline.in/city-guide/hospitals-in-faridabad|archive-date=25 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The city also has one Government Medical College Hospital named \n[[Employees State Insurance Corporation Medical College, Faridabad]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esicmcfbd.ac.in|title=ESIC Medical College,Faridabad, Haryana|website=www.esicmcfbd.ac.in|access-date=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128164600/http://www.esicmcfbd.ac.in/|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Asian Institute of Medical Sciences]]\n* [[ESIC Medical College, Faridabad|ESIC Medical College]]\n* Fortis Escorts Hospital\n*[[Metro Hospital|Metro Heart Institute Hospital]]\n* QRG Central Hospital & Research Centre\n* Sarvodaya Hospital & Research Centre\n* RG Stone Urology & Laparoscopy Hospital\n* IBS Ashwani Hospital\n* Park Hospital\n* [[Badshah Khan Hospital]] popularly known as BK Hospital\n* QRG Health City\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Sports==\n\n===Cricket===\n[[File:Nahar Singh Stadium.jpg|thumb|Nahar Singh Stadium]]\nThe cricket stadium in the city is [[Nahar Singh Stadium]], which [[seating capacity|seats]] approx. 25,000 and has hosted 8 international cricket matches<ref name=tribuneindia190302 /> and a league cricket match between [[Mumbai Heroes]] and Bhojpuri Dabbang of [[Celebrity Cricket League]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}} However, owing to the poor condition of the grounds, international competitions have not been held there since 2006.<ref name=tribuneindia190302 /><ref>{{Cite news | url = http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/all-is-not-lost-for-nahar-singh-stadium/160189/ | title = All is not lost for Nahar Singh Stadium | last = Vivek | first = G.S. | date = 22 June 2007 | newspaper = [[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> In 2019, a $10.15 million (115 Crore) Haryana government project began to renovate the stadium and grounds.  International matches are expected to resume in the facility by the early 2020.<ref name=tribuneindia190302>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/haryana-tribune/cricket-matches-to-resume-in-faridabad-stadium-next-year/736970.html|title=Cricket matches to resume in Faridabad stadium next year|first=Bijendra|last=Ahlawat|date=2 March 2019|website=Haryana Tribune|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Tourism ==\n\n=== Badkhal Lake ===\n[[File:Dried Badkhal lake.jpg|thumb|Dried Badkhal lake]]\n{{Main|Badkhal Lake}}\nBadkhal Lake was located in Badkhal village, 8&nbsp;km from Delhi Border. The lake fringed by Aravalli hills was a man-made embankment which has now dried up.<ref>{{citation|title=Badkhal lake in Faridabad on way to revival|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/the-good-earth/Badkhal-lake-in-Faridabad-on-way-to-revival/articleshow/47581665.cms|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=8 June 2015|agency=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|access-date=10 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609193304/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/the-good-earth/Badkhal-lake-in-Faridabad-on-way-to-revival/articleshow/47581665.cms|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The lake complex, spread over 40 acres, had come up in 1969.<ref>{{citation|title=CM at BJP rally may look at Badkhal lake revival|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/haryana/politics/cm-at-bjp-rally-may-look-at-badkhal-lake-revival/90427.html|publisher=Tribune|date=7 June 2015|access-date=10 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063246/http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/haryana/politics/cm-at-bjp-rally-may-look-at-badkhal-lake-revival/90427.html|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2015, Haryana government decided to revive the Badkhal lake here to once again attract tourists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/the-good-earth/Badkhal-lake-in-Faridabad-on-way-to-revival/articleshow/47581665.cms|title=Badkhal lake in Faridabad on way to revival|work=The Times of India|access-date=10 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609193304/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/the-good-earth/Badkhal-lake-in-Faridabad-on-way-to-revival/articleshow/47581665.cms|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Surajkund Tourist Complex and International Crafts Fair ===\n{{main|Surajkund}}\n[[File:LTD7K 5601 resize.JPG|thumb|right|SurajKund International Crafts Fair, Faridabad]]\nSituated at a distance of around 8&nbsp;km from South Delhi. It is a 10th-century water reservoir which believed to be built by Tomar king Surajpal.<ref name=\"Gupta1987\">{{cite book|author=Vijay Kumar Gupta|title=Tourism in India|url=https://archive.org/details/tourisminindia0000gupt|url-access=registration|year=1987|publisher=Gyan Publishing House|isbn=978-81-212-0124-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/tourisminindia0000gupt/page/27 27]\u2013|access-date=30 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_tktd_haryana_surajkund.asp |title=Suraj Kund - Ticketed Monument - Archaeological Survey of India |publisher=Asi.nic.in |access-date=2015-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091011023435/http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_tktd_haryana_surajkund.asp |archive-date=11 October 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Place is known for its annual fair \"Surajkund International Crafts Mela\".<ref>{{citation|title=Haryana to promote farmhouse tourism during Surajkund Mela|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/lifestyle/haryana-to-promote-farmhouse-tourism-during-surajkund-mela-1018977.html|publisher=IBN Live|date=11 July 2015|access-date=10 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150714024756/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/lifestyle/haryana-to-promote-farmhouse-tourism-during-surajkund-mela-1018977.html|archive-date=14 July 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 2015 edition of fair was visited by 1.2 million visitors including 160,000 foreigners with more than 20 countries participating in fair.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/others-news/29th-surajkund-international-crafts-mela-ends-739828 |title=29th Surajkund International Crafts Mela Ends |publisher=Ndtv.com |access-date=2015-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124133726/http://www.ndtv.com/others-news/29th-surajkund-international-crafts-mela-ends-739828 |archive-date=24 November 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Suraj Kund Lake<ref>[http://www.d2i.in/visit/Surajkund-Crafts-Mela_Suraj-Kund_Faridabad_Attractions/3391 D2I \u2013 Doors 2 India. Surajkund Crafts Mela, Suraj Kund, Faridabad] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721155452/http://www.d2i.in/visit/Surajkund-Crafts-Mela_Suraj-Kund_Faridabad_Attractions/3391 |date=21 July 2011 }}. D2i.in. Retrieved on 2012-01-10.</ref> here is surrounded by rock cut steps.\n\n2016 edition of Surajkund International Crafts Mela will be the 30th edition and People's Republic of China will be participating in the fair.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/festival/surajkund-international-crafts-mela/|title=32nd Surajkund International Crafts Mela Begins|publisher=BookMyShow|access-date=2018-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120065816/https://in.bookmyshow.com/festival/surajkund-international-crafts-mela/|archive-date=20 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Participation of the China will be the part of agreement signed between India and China in 2014 to celebrate year 2016 as \"Year of China in India\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/china-to-showcase-artifacts-in-haryana-s-surajkund-fair-115102701301_1.html |title=China to showcase artifacts in Haryana's Surajkund fair &#124; Business Standard News |publisher=Business-standard.com |access-date=2015-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028150525/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/china-to-showcase-artifacts-in-haryana-s-surajkund-fair-115102701301_1.html |archive-date=28 October 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Anangpur Dam===\n{{main|Anagpur Dam}}\n[[File:Surajkund dam \"downstream\" side.jpg|thumb|Surajkund dam downstream side]]\nThe Anagpur Dam, located close to the Anagpur village (also called Arangpur) in [[Faridabad district]] of [[Haryana]], India, is {{convert|2|km|mi}} away from the more famous [[Surajkund]].{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nThis unique Indian hydraulic engineering structure was built during the reign of King [[Anangpal]] of the [[Tomar dynasty]] in 8th century. It is approachable by road from [[Delhi]] from the Delhi \u2013 [[Mathura]] road. The ruins of the fortifications found in Anangpur village establishes by an inference that it was built by Anangpal as part of the [[Lal Kot]] that was developed as the first city of Delhi in the 8th century.<ref name=Sharma>{{Cite book|last=Sharma|first=Y.D|title=Delhi and its Neighbourhood|work=Surjakund and Anagpur Dam|pages=100\u2013161|access-date=2009-09-05|publisher=Archaeological Survey of India|location=New Delhi|year=2001|url=http://www.indiaclub.com/Shop/SearchResults.asp?ProdStock=8780|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030426012208/http://www.indiaclub.com/Shop/SearchResults.asp?ProdStock=8780|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 April 2003|quote=Page 100:Suraj Kund lies about 3&nbsp;km south-east of Tughlaqabad in district Gurgaon\u2014The reservoir is believed to have been constructed in the tenth century by King Surjapal of Tomar dynasty, whose existence is based on Bardic tradition. Page 101: About 2&nbsp;km south-west of Surajkund, close to the village of Anagpur (also called Arangpur) is a dam ascribed to Anagpal of the Tomar Dynasty, who is also credited with building the [[Lal Kot]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Peck>{{Cite book|last=Peck|first=Lucy|title= Delhi \u2013 A thousand years of Building|work= Suraj Kund dam and Surajkund tank|page=29|publisher=Roli Books Pvt Ltd.|location=New Delhi|year=2005|isbn=81-7436-354-8|url=https://www.vedamsbooks.com/no43813.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060312215021/https://www.vedamsbooks.com/no43813.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-03-12|access-date=2009-09-05|quote=One of the two significant structures in the area, the dam lies about 1&nbsp;km to the north of the Anangpur village. A path from the main village street will lead you in to flat pastureland. Head for the small rocky hill ahead of you and climb over it. On the other side is another flat area, rather thickly covered in thorn trees. It is worth finding a way through them to the dam that straddles the gap between the two nearby hills. The dam is an impressive edifice 50&nbsp;m wide and 7&nbsp;m high built from accurately hewn quartzite blocks.---There is a passage for the egress of water at the level of the ground on the dammed side. The flat land across which you have walked is clearly caused by centuries of silt deposits in the lake that once existed behind this dam. The land around has been vwey heavily quarried recently, so further archaeological finds are unlikely.}}</ref><ref name=anag>{{Citation |url=http://www.indiainfoweb.com/haryana/lakes/anagpur-dam.html |title=Anangpur Dam |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125185110/http://www.indiainfoweb.com/haryana/lakes/anagpur-dam.html |archive-date=25 November 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n=== Recreation ===\nFaridabad and various shopping malls including SRS Mall in Sector 12, Crown Interiorz Mall in Sector 37, Crown Plaza in Sector 15 A, Parasnath Mall along with several others. The city has good network of parks in each sector with some of the major parks like Town Park in Sector 12 which also accommodates one of the Largest [[Flag of India]]. Omaxe World street is the recent addition to the malls of [[Greater faridabad]]\n\n==Religious sites==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Shri Salasar Balaji Evam Khatu Shyam Mandir Situated on Main Mathura Road, Ballabhgarh Faridabad\n* Shri 1008 Parshvanath Digambar Jain Mandir in Sector 16<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jaintemple.in/temples/india/faridabad|title=Digamber Jain Temples in Faridabad \u2013 Faridabad Digamber Jain Temples -Digamber Jain Mandir in Faridabad|access-date=7 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307072537/http://jaintemple.in/temples/india/faridabad|archive-date=7 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Jharna Mandir village Mohabbtabad\n* Nagashri Temple in Sihi\n* Peer Ratan Nath Dargah Mandir\n* Sai Baba Mandir in Sector 16A\n* Sharon Fellowship Church in Sector 23 \n* Shiv Mandir in Sainik Colony\n* Shri Triveni Hanuman Mandir at Gurgaon-Faridabad Expressway\n* Parson Temple near Badhkal Lake<ref>https://www.tripadvisor.in/Attraction_Review-g677469-d8837240-Reviews-Parson_Temple-Faridabad_Faridabad_District_Haryana.html</ref>\n* Jagannath Temple in Sector 16\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Utilities==\nFaridabad has been selected as one of the 100 [[Smart Cities in India]].<ref>{{citation |title=Faridabad is a proud participant in the Indian Smart Cities Challenge |url=http://smartcitieschallenge.in/city/faridabad |access-date=9 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831005348/http://smartcitieschallenge.in/city/faridabad |archive-date=31 August 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A live talk show on making Faridabad 'a smart city' was organised at Municipal Corporation's Auditorium.{{when|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{citation |title=Live talk show on Smart City project held in Faridabad |url=http://www.iamin.in/en/faridabad/news/live-talk-show-smart-city-project-held-faridabad-71855 |access-date=7 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151011013121/http://www.iamin.in/en/faridabad/news/live-talk-show-smart-city-project-held-faridabad-71855 |archive-date=11 October 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=\u092b\u0930\u0940\u0926\u093e\u092c\u093e\u0926 \u0921\u093f\u0935\u0947\u0932\u092a\u092e\u0947\u0902\u091f \u0905\u0925\u0949\u0930\u093f\u091f\u0940 \u091c\u0932\u094d\u0926! |url=http://navbharattimes.indiatimes.com/state/punjab-and-haryana/faridabad/faridabad-development-authority-soon/articleshow/49244993.cms |work=[[Navbharat Times]] |date=7 October 2015 |access-date=12 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405083810/http://navbharattimes.indiatimes.com/state/punjab-and-haryana/faridabad/faridabad-development-authority-soon/articleshow/49244993.cms |archive-date=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Haryana Power Generation Corporation]] Ltd (HPGCL) is setting up a solar power plant at the site of a defunct thermal power plant in Faridabad. The power generator plans to set up the plant over 151.78 acres near Bata Chowk in the district that generated coal based energy in the past.<ref>{{citation |title=Haryana aims to install solar plants to replace old thermal plants |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2016-03-15/news/71543274_1_power-plant-solar-plant-hpgcl |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=15 March 2016 |access-date=24 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405034650/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2016-03-15/news/71543274_1_power-plant-solar-plant-hpgcl |archive-date=5 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\nA petition was filed with [[National Green Tribunal Act|National Green Tribunal]] (NGT) for protection of [[Aravalli Range|Aravalli]] from Faridabad waste disposal.<ref>{{citation|title=Activists move NGT to save Aravalli in Faridabad, Gurgaon|url=http://wap.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/activists-move-ngt-to-save-aravalli-in-faridabad-gurgaon-115092300045_1.html|access-date=7 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211195817/http://wap.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/activists-move-ngt-to-save-aravalli-in-faridabad-gurgaon-115092300045_1.html|archive-date=11 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Politics of Faridabad ==\nThe [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha]] from Faridabad is [[Krishan Pal Gurjar]] elected in May 2019, and member of [[Vidhan Sabha]] is Narendar Gupta elected in October 2019.{{Citation needed|date= October 2019}}\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2018}}\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n* [[Ram Chander Bainda]] \u2013 Indian politician\n* [[Avtar Singh Bhadana]], politician,<ref>{{cite news|url=Faridabad ex-MP to contest UP assembly polls \u2013 Times of India}}</ref>\n* [[Rahul Dalal]], b 1992 \u2013 cricketer.\n* [[Krishan Pal Gurjar]], politician<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.krishanpalgurjar.com/biography.php|title=Archived copy|access-date=15 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118005513/http://www.krishanpalgurjar.com/biography.php|archive-date=18 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Himani Kapoor]], b 1988 \u2013 singer\n* [[Ajey Nagar]] \u2013 Carryminati  \u2013 Famous Youtuber\n* [[Lalit Nagar]] - Politician - MLA from Tigaon constituency\n* [[Nikhil Nanda]] \u2013 Industrialist\n* [[Sonu Nigam]], b 1973 \u2013 playback singer\n* [[Ajay Ratra]], b 1981 \u2013 former international cricketer\n* [[Mahesh Rawat]], b 1985 \u2013 cricketer\n* [[Anisa Sayyed]] \u2013 shooter\n* [[Richa Sharma (singer)|Richa Sharma]], b 1980 \u2013 playback and devotional singer\n* [[Mahender Pratap Singh]] \u2013 Indian politician\n* [[Rahul Tewatia]] \u2013 cricketer -Haryana-Kings Xl Punjab \u2013 from Sihi Village\n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Only add a person to this list if they already have their own article on the English Wikipedia \u2666\u2666\u2666---> \n<!---\u2666\u2666\u2666 Please keep the list in alphabetical order by LAST NAME \u2666\u2666\u2666--->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Delhi]]\n* [[Delhi NCR]]\n* [[Haryana]]\n* [[Chandigarh]]\n* [[Gurgaon]]\n* [[Noida]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*http://www.FaridabadYellowPages.com \u2013 A 2 Z about Faridabad\n*{{citation|title = The Imperial Gazetteer of India, Vol. 12|chapter = Faridabad|publisher = Oxford at Clarendon Press|year = 1909|page = 51|chapter-url = http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V12_057.gif|ref = Hi|title-link = The Imperial Gazetteer of India}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://faridabad.nic.in/ District Faridabad Official Web Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150927074038/https://www.mcfbd.com/ Municipal Corporation of Faridabad Official Website]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n\n{{Million-plus cities in India}}\n{{National Capital Territory of Delhi}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Smart cities in India]]\n[[Category:Faridabad]]\n[[Category:Faridabad district]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Faridabad district]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Haryana]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Haryana]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Haryana]]\n[[Category:Rebuilt buildings and structures in India]]\n", "name_user": "Rockpiremonk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faridabad"}
{"title_page": "Philippine Science High School SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox school \n| name                = Philippine Science High School - SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus\n| native_name         = \n| motto               = \"Weaving the Culture of Science, Mathematics, and Technology in SOCCSKSARGEN\" \n| logo                = [[File:PSHS System Logo.png|100px]]\n| image               = [[File:PSHS-SRC Acad 2.jpg|300px]]\n| caption             = Academic Building 2\n| type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] Specialized High School\n| established         = February 3, 2012\n| opened              = June 17, 2013 \n| streetaddress       = Brgy. Paraiso     \n| city                = [[Koronadal, South Cotabato]]\n| country             = {{PHL}}\n| zipcode             = 9506\n| coordinates         = {{coord|6.488865|124.816596|display=inline,title}}\n| affiliation         = [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|Department of Science and Technology]]\n| campus director     = Dr. Chuchi P. Garganera, PhD\n| test_name           = PSHS National Competitive Examination (PSHS NCE)\n| enrollment          = 501 (Academic Year 2018-2019)\n| faculty             = 70\n| grades              = [[Seventh grade|7]] to [[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| newspaper           = '''The Twelfth Quill''' ''and'' '''Pisay Pluma'''\n| language            = [[English language|English]], [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n| nickname            = PISAY-SRC\n| song                = PSHS Hymn\n| website             = {{URL|src.pshs.edu.ph}}\n}}\n\n'''Philippine Science High School - SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus''' (PSHS-SRC), situated at Brgy. Paraiso, [[Koronadal City]], is the 12th campus of the [[Philippine Science High School System]] which admits and grants scholarships to students who are gifted in science and mathematics all over [[SOCCSKSARGEN]] and neighboring places. Admission to this campus is by passing the National Competitive Examination organized and conducted by the PSHS System annually and only [[Philippines|Filipino]] citizens are qualified to attend. SOCCSKSARGEN covers the provinces of [[South Cotabato]], [[North Cotabato]], [[Sarangani]] and [[Sultan Kudarat]]. The PSHS-SRC formally opened on June 17, 2013 with 52 scholars comprising as the pioneering batch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pshs.edu.ph/11-feature/140-pshs-src-opens-for-the-pioneer-batch |title=PSHS-SRC opens for the pioneer batch |publisher=Pshs.edu.ph |accessdate=2015-07-10}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Philippine Science High School System History===\nThe first Philippine Science High School was established in Diliman, Quezon City under Republic Act No. 3661, known as the PSHS Charter. The school opened on 5 September 1964 at a rented building owned by the Philippine Government Employees Association along Elliptical Road, Diliman, Quezon City. It was only in 1970 that the school moved to its present campus along Agham Road, Diliman, Quezon City.  In 1997, the PSHS System Law (R.A. 8496) was signed by President Fidel V. Ramos. It established the PSHS System and unified all the existing campuses into a single system of governance and management. In 2001, the PSHS System Law was further amended by R.A. No. 9036 consolidating the power and authority over all PSHS System campuses into a single Board of Trustees to ensure uniform policy coordination, standards and management.\n\n===SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus===\nPSHS-SRC was founded on '''February 3, 2012''' by virtue of '''BOT Resolution No. 2012-02-04''' to ensure optimum distribution of opportunities for Science & Technology-gifted in Region XII and neighboring areas. The campus formally opened on '''June 17, 2013''' with a pioneering batch consisting 52 Filipino scholars. Since 2013 to present, SRC has been under the tutelage of Dr. Chuchi P. Garganera, Campus Director.\n\n==Admission==\nGrade 6 students who belong to the top 10% of the class or must have special aptitude in Science & Mathematics must take and perform well in the '''NCE''', the admission test of the Philippine Science High School System, also indicating their interest in the SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus.\n\n===National Competitive Examination===\nAdmission to the PSHS System is through the PSHS System National Competitive Examination (PSHS-NCE). The screening consists of tests in Verbal, Abstract Reasoning, Science and Mathematics. To be eligible for admission, applicants must be Filipino students who must belong to the top 10% of the graduating class or must have special aptitude in science and math. The top 90 scholars from the region are admitted as scholars.\n\n===Lateral Admissions Qualifying Examination===\n\nA student who has finished Grade 7 / Grade 8 (under the high school curriculum or the new K-12 curriculum) outside of the PSHS System may be allowed admission/entry to the PSHS by passing the Lateral Admissions Qualifying Examination. It annually occurs during summer before the new Academic School year starts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Philippine.Science.High.School.System/photos/a.1656265191275219.1073741828.1641038776131194/1759578804277190/?type=3&theater}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\n\n[[File:SRC-Administration.png|thumb|upright=2.4|this is the administration of PSHS-SRC]]\n\n===Board of Trustees===\nThe Board of Trustees is the highest policy-making body of the PSHS System. It coordinates with the Executive Committee for the implementation of these policies. It is composed of eight ex officio members and five private sector representatives, chaired by the DOST secretary.\n\n===Office of the Executive Director===\nThe Office of the Executive Director is the personal office of the head of the direct service administration and chief planner of the system. The OED recommends policies and guidelines for the consideration of the Board of Trustees. The Executive Director spearheads the Executive Committee, which is composed of the different directors belonging to different campuses. The Executive Council is the collegial body \u2013 composed of the Executive Director, the Deputy Executive Director, the Main Campus Director, and the Regional Campus Directors.\n\n===Office of the Campus Director===\n===Curriculum & Instruction Services Division===\n===Finance & Administrative Division===\nThe Finance and Administration Division is responsible for providing financial and administrative support to the whole school system. Among these include budgeting and accounting, as well as procurement and contracting of goods and services.\n\n===Student Services Division===\nThe Student Services Division handles the different branches of the school in charge of rendering suitable services and benefits, as well as providing for its students and their welfare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://src.pshs.edu.ph/ |title=Administration &#124; PSHS SOCCSKSARGEN Region Campus |publisher=Src.pshs.edu.ph |date=2015-09-09 |accessdate=2015-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n===Special Curriculum===\nThe PSHS-SRC follows the same special curriculum prescribed and designated by the Philippine Science High School System. The core curriculum is packed with Science, Mathematics, and Technology courses.\n\nThe names of each section in each grade level correspond to a theme based on the major subject offered in that particular grade level. (Earth Science for Grade 7, Biology for Grade 8, Chemistry for Grade 9, and Physics for Grade 10) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pshs.edu.ph/curriculum/ |title=PSHS 6-Year Curriculum Subject Matrix |publisher=pshs.edu.ph |date= |accessdate=2015-07-10}}</ref>\n\n====Grade 7 (Gemstones)====\n* '''[[Diamond]]'''\n* '''[[Sapphire]]'''\n* '''[[Ruby]]'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n! Subject\n! Title\n! Code\n|-\n! style=\"background:#D1E8EF\" | Integrated Sciences 1\n| style=\"background:#98FB98;\" | Investigating Our Surroundings\n| style=\"background:#FBF373;\" | IS 