character of Georg Aadniel Kiir in the films  ''[[Spring (1969 film)|Kevade]]'' (Spring) (1970), ''[[Suvi (film)|Suvi]]'' (Summer) (1976) ''[[S\u00fcgis (film)|S\u00fcgis]]'' (Autumn) (1991), and ''Talve'' (Winter) (2020), all directed by [[Arvo Kruusement]], apart from ''Talve'', and based on a series of novels by [[Oskar Luts]].\n\n'''Filmography'''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Genre\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1970 || ''[[Kevade]]'' || [[drama film|drama]] || Kiir ||\n|-\n|1976 || ''[[Suvi (film)|Suvi]]'' ||[[comedy-drama]] ||  Kiir ||\n|-\n|1991 || ''[[S\u00fcgis]]'' || [[comedy-drama]] || Kiir ||\n|-\n|2020 || ''[[Talve (film)|Talve]]'' || [[comedy-drama]] || Kiir ||\n|-\n|}\n\n===Radio acting===\nFor many years, he performed, together with [[Raimo Aas]], in ''[[Meelejahutaja]]''., a Sunday morning [[radio]] programme.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010|reason=also, clarify...what type of radio acting?   is this where the \"comedian\" occupation enters?  no wiki article on the program yet and wiki article on Aas is unclear as well.}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0503191}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lepa, Margus}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Estonian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Estonian male radio actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Estonian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tallinn]]\n[[Category:People from Tallinn]]\n[[Category:Estonian journalists]]\n[[Category:Estonian Academy of Music and Theatre alumni]]\n<!--[[Category:Estonian comedians]]--hidden at September 2010 - no mention, with/without attribution, in prose-->\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n\n{{Estonia-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cardiffbear88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margus_Lepa"}
{"title_page": "Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez", "text_new": "{{short description|Nicaraguan wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Nicaraguan\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1968|4|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Managua]], Nicaragua\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez Mej\u00eda''' (born 14 April 1968) is a Nicaraguan [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 100 kg|men's freestyle 100 kg]] at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/gu/magdiel-gutierrez-1.html |title=Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez Olympic Results |accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutierrez, Magdiel}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Managua]]\n{{Nicaragua-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nicaraguan wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Nicaraguan\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1968|4|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Managua]], Nicaragua\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez Mej\u00eda''' (born 14 April 1968) is a Nicaraguan [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1992 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 100 kg|men's freestyle 100 kg]] at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/gu/magdiel-gutierrez-1.html |title=Magdiel Guti\u00e9rrez Olympic Results |accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gutierrez, Magdiel}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Nicaragua]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1992 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Managua]]\n{{Nicaragua-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magdiel_Guti%C3%A9rrez"}
{"title_page": "Syledis", "text_new": "'''Syledis''' ('''SY'''stem '''LE'''ger pour mesure la '''DIS'''tance) was a terrestrial [[radio navigation]] and locating system. The system operated in the [[UHF]] segment of 420-450 MHz. It was manufactured in France by Sercel S.A. and was operational during the 1980s and until about 1995, providing positioning and navigational support for the petroleum sector in the [[North Sea]] and to other scientific projects. Syledis has been replaced by [[Global Positioning System|GPS]].\n\n==Functioning==\nDetermination of the position of mobile vehicles, like f.e. [[Watercraft|vessels]], using Syledis is accomplished by measurement of [[Ergodic theory|transit time]] of [[radio wave]]s between mobiles and [[Radio broadcasting|radio stations]] at known points. There are two modes of operation, ''active range mode'' and ''passive pseudo-range mode''.\n\n===Further explanation of the functioning of the Syledis positioning system===\nA vessel is equipped with a transmitter that transmits a coded signal to at least three [[Electric beacon|radio beacons]] each placed at a known point. The beacons send the code back to the transmitter. The returned coded signal is placed in a [[timeslot]] to determine the origin of the returned code. Therefore, in an earlier stage a specified timeslot is connected to a specific beacon.\n\nThe elapsed time is proportional to twice the distance between the transmitter and the beacons. After the distance to the beacons is derived the position of the vessel can be calculated. The transmitter computes the distances to the beacons and a computer, connected with the transmitter, computes the position of the vessel.\n\n====Possible causes for measurement inaccuracy====\nThe Syledis system has a measurement sensitivity that can be expressed in centimeters. Due to wheater conditions the wave propagation speed, for electromagnetic waves in air almost the [[speed of light]], can change. In wet conditions, rain or snow, the wave propagation is a little bit slower than in dry conditions. So that gives an inaccuracy in determining the correct position of the vessel.\n\nAnother important factor is the length of the cables used to connect the [[antenna (radio)|antennas]] with the radio beacons at the shore, for example placed on [[lighthouse]]s, or on [[oil rig platform|oil rig platforms]] and the cable(s) to connect the antenna with the transmitter at the vessel. Normally the antenna will be placed at the top of the mast and the transmitter wil be placed in the [[Bridge (nautical)|wheelhouse]], where the captain and the mate can see the displays of the transmitter. \nThose cables has to be [[Calibration|calibrated]] in order to obtain the smallest possible [[measurement uncertainty]].\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUl-NvaCHmkC&pg=PA115&dq=Syledis|author=R.P. Loweth|title=Manual of Offshore Surveying for Geoscientists and Engineers|publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]]|edition=1st|year=1997|page=115|isbn=0-412-80550-2|lccn=96-72156}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TW5WAAAAMAAJ&q=Syledis&dq=Syledis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JmzGUb6FOMm30AGr2ICgCg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA|title=Wireless World|publisher=Dorset House|volume=89|year=1983|page=73}}\n\n[[Category:Measurement]]\n[[Category:Geolocation]]\n[[Category:Radio navigation]]\n[[Category:Tracking]]\n[[Category:Ubiquitous computing]]\n[[Category:Wireless locating]]\n\n\n{{Radio-comm-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Syledis''' ('''SY'''stem '''LE'''ger pour mesure la '''DIS'''tance) was a terrestrial [[radio navigation]] and locating system. The system operated in the [[UHF]] segment of 420-450 MHz. It was manufactured in France by Sercel S.A. and was operational during the 1980s and until about 1995, providing positioning and navigational support for the petroleum sector in the [[North Sea]] and to other scientific projects. Syledis has been replaced by [[Global Positioning System|GPS]].\n\n==Functioning==\nDetermination of the position of mobile vehicles, like f.e. [[Watercraft|vessels]], using Syledis is accomplished by measurement of [[Ergodic theory|transit time]] of [[radio wave]]s between mobiles and [[Radio broadcasting|radio stations]] at known points. There are two modes of operation, ''active range mode'' and ''passive pseudo-range mode''.\n\n===Further explanation of the functioning of the Syledis positioning system===\nA vessel is equipped with a transmitter that transmits a coded signal to at least three [[Electric beacon|radio beacons]] each placed at a known point. The beacons send the code back to the transmitter. The returned coded signal is placed in a [[timeslot]] to determine the origin of the returned code. Therefore, in an earlier stage a specified timeslot is connected to a specific beacon.\n\nThe elapsed time is proportional to twice the distance between the transmitter and the beacons. After the distance to the beacons is derived the position of the vessel can be calculated. The transmitter computes the distances to the beacons and a computer, connected with the transmitter, computes the position of the vessel.\n\n====Possible causes for measurement inaccuracy====\nThe Syledis system has a measurement sensitivity that can be expressed in centimeters. Due to wheater conditions the wave propagation speed, for electromagnetic waves in air almost the [[speed of light]], can change. In wet conditions, rain or snow, the wave propagation is a little bit slower than in dry conditions. So that gives an inaccuracy in determining the correct position of the vessel.\n\nAn other important factor is the length of the cables used to connect the [[antenna (radio)|antennas]] with the radio beacons at the shore, for example placed on [[lighthouse]]s, or on [[oil rig platform|oil rig platforms]] and the cable(s) to connect the antenna with the transmitter at the vessel. Normally the antenna will be placed at the top of the mast and the transmitter wil be placed in the [[Bridge (nautical)|wheelhouse]], where the captain and the mate can see the displays of the transmitter. \nThose cables has to be [[Calibration|calibrated]] in order to obtain the smallest possible [[measurement uncertainty]].\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUl-NvaCHmkC&pg=PA115&dq=Syledis|author=R.P. Loweth|title=Manual of Offshore Surveying for Geoscientists and Engineers|publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]]|edition=1st|year=1997|page=115|isbn=0-412-80550-2|lccn=96-72156}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TW5WAAAAMAAJ&q=Syledis&dq=Syledis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JmzGUb6FOMm30AGr2ICgCg&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA|title=Wireless World|publisher=Dorset House|volume=89|year=1983|page=73}}\n\n[[Category:Measurement]]\n[[Category:Geolocation]]\n[[Category:Radio navigation]]\n[[Category:Tracking]]\n[[Category:Ubiquitous computing]]\n[[Category:Wireless locating]]\n\n\n{{Radio-comm-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePossible causes for measurement inaccuracy:Typo fixing, replaced: An other  \u2192 Another", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syledis"}
{"title_page": "Action 52", "text_new": "{{short description|Unlicensed multicart video game compilation}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n|title          = Action 52\n|image          = Action 52 (NES) box art.jpg\n|caption        = NES cover art\n|developer      = [[Active Enterprises]] <small>(NES)</small><br>[[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] <small>(Genesis)</small>\n|publisher      = Active Enterprises\n|director       = Vince Perri<br />[[Jay Obernolte]] {{small|(Genesis)}}\n|producer       = Vince Perri<br />Raul Gomila<br />Jay Obernolte {{small|(Genesis)}}\n|designer       = Mario Gonzalez {{small|(NES)}}\n|programmer     = Albert Hernandez<br />Cronos Engineering, Inc.\n|artist         = Javier Perez\n|writer         = Mario Gonzalez {{small|(NES)}}\n|composer       = '''NES''':<br />Mario Gonzalez<br />Javier Perez<br />[[Ed Bogas]] {{small|(uncredited)}}<br />'''Genesis''':<br />Nu Romantic Productions (Mark Steven Miller and Jason Scher)\n|series         = \n|released       = '''NES'''<br><sup>'''[[North America|NA]]'''</sup> [[1991 in video gaming|1991]]<br>'''Sega Genesis'''<br><sup>'''[[North America|NA]]'''</sup> [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]<br>'''SNES'''<br><sup>Cancelled</sup>\n|genre          = Various\n|modes          = [[Single-player]] <br> [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms      = [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] <br> [[Sega Genesis]]\n}}\n'''''Action 52''''' is an unlicensed [[multicart]] [[video game]] compilation developed by Active Enterprises for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], and [[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] for the [[Sega Genesis]]. The NES version was released in 1991, followed by the Genesis version in 1993. A  [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] version was advertised in magazines, but never released. Active Enterprises was legally incorporated in the Bahamas, however, offices and development were located in Miami, Florida while the company's product warehousing was located in Orlando, Florida.\n\n''Action 52'' consists of 52 games that cover a variety of [[video game genre|genres]], with the most common being [[Shoot 'em up|scrolling shooter]]s and [[platform game|platformer]]s.<ref name=\"Action 52 for NES - MobyGames\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/action-52 |publisher=[[MobyGames]] |title=Action 52 for NES - MobyGames |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref> One of the more notable games is ''[[The Cheetahmen]]'', Active's attempt at creating a franchise similar to the [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]].\n\nThe NES version of ''Action 52'' became notorious among gamers for the poor quality and functionality of its games, and is often considered to be the [[List of video games notable for negative reception|worst game of all time]]. The Genesis version is widely considered superior, though still of subpar quality. Many [[Video game collecting|video game collectors]] value ''Action 52'' for its notoriety and rarity. It initially retailed for the comparatively high price of [[USD|US$]]199 ({{Inflation|US|199|1991|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gamespy.com/top10/december02/shame/index2.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414065846/http://archive.gamespy.com/top10/december02/shame/index2.shtml|archivedate=2009-04-14 |title=Top Ten Shameful Games |publisher=Archive.gamespy.com |date=2002-12-31 |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n\n===NES===\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:70%\"\n! style=\"width:14em; text-align:left;\" | '''List of games'''\n! |\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n\n# Fire Breathers\n# Star Evil\n# Illuminator\n# G-Force Fighters\n# Ooze\n# Silver Sword\n# Critical Bypass\n# Jupiter Scope\n# Alfredo (\"Alfred N the Fettuc\" on the title screen, widely known to be \"Alfredo and the Fettuccine\")\n# Operation Full-Moon\n# Dam Busters\n# Thrusters\n# Haunted Hill (\"Haunted Halls\" on the title screen, \"Haunted Halls of Wentworth\" in the manual)\n# Chill Out\n# Sharks\n# Megalonia\n# French Baker\n# Atmos Quake\n# Meong\n# Space Dreams\n# Streemerz (lacks its title on the title screen)\n# Spread Fire\n# Bubblegum Rosy (\"Bubblegum Rossie\" on the title screen)\n# Micro Mike (\"Micro-Mike\" on the title screen)\n# Underground\n# Rocket Jock (\"Rocket Jockey\" on the title screen)\n# Non Human\n# Cry Baby\n# Slashers\n# Crazy Shuffle\n# Fuzz Power\n# Shooting Gallery\n# Lollipops (\"Lollipop\" on the title screen)\n# Evil Empire\n# Sombreros\n# Storm Over the Desert\n# Mash Man\n# They Came (\"They Came...\" on the title screen)\n# Lazer League\n# Billy Bob (lacks its title on the title screen)\n# City of Doom\n# Bits and Pieces\n# Beeps and Blips\n# Manchester Beat\n# The Boss\n# Dedant\n# Hambo (\"Hambo's Adventures\" on the title screen)\n# Time Warp Tickers\n# Jigsaw\n# Ninja Assault\n# Robbie Robot (\"Robbie N the Robots\" on the title screen)\n# The Cheetahmen (\"Action Gamemaster\" on the title screen)\n\n|}\n[[File:Hauntedhills.png|thumb|left|Gameplay of ''Haunted Halls of Wentworth'' from the NES version (1991) of ''Action 52''.]]\nThe games on the NES version cover a variety of [[video game genre|genres]], the most common being [[shoot 'em up|vertical shooters]] set in outer space and [[platform game|platformers]].<ref name=\"Action 52 for NES - MobyGames\"/> The games have major [[glitch]]es, some of which cause them to freeze or crash due to programming flaws; there are also incomplete or endless levels, confusing design and unresponsive controls. In the manual, each game has a one-sentence description, with some being described as completely different games and others incorrectly described or categorized.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nThe \"featured\" game of ''Action 52'' was ''[[The Cheetahmen]]''. There were initial plans for a line of merchandise including action figures, T-shirts, a comic book series, and a television cartoon based on the characters (an advertisement for ''Cheetahmen'' action figures, displaying prototype sketches, was included in the aforementioned comic book).<ref name=\"Active Exposed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/active.html |title=Active Enterprises exposed |publisher=atarihq.com |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52stuff.htm |title=Action 52 - th' Stuff |publisher=Arkfullofsorrow.com |accessdate=2009-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110913045933/http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52stuff.htm |archivedate=2011-09-13 }}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> However, these plans quickly fell through as [[word of mouth]] and reviews mounted after the game's release.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nA [[Yeah! Woo!]] [[Break (music)|drum break]] that is sampled from [[Rob Base and DJ E-Z Rock|Rob Base]]'s song \"[[It Takes Two (Rob Base & DJ E-Z Rock song)|It Takes Two]]\" is used, only in the opening sequence of the NES version.<ref>{{Citation|title = Action 52 - Angry Video Game Nerd - Episode 90|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a4QBeADNM34&t=167|date = 2011-07-21|accessdate = 2016-02-21|last = Cinemassacre}}</ref>\n\nActive Enterprises advertised a competition in which anyone who could complete level 5 of ''Ooze'' would be entered into a prize drawing to win $104,000 ($52,000 cash, and a scholarship of the same value). The game was reported to crash on level 2, making this prize impossible to win<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/games/columns/67085/The-Hall-of-Shame-01.17.08:-Action-52.htm |title=411mania.com: Games - The Hall of Shame 01.17.08: Action 52 |date=2008-01-17 |author=Chiucchi, Vincent |publisher=411mania.com |accessdate=2009-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100506075008/http://www.411mania.com/games/columns/67085/The-Hall-of-Shame-01.17.08:-Action-52.htm |archivedate=2010-05-06 }}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> without the use of an emulator or an in-game exploit, rendering the contest a failure.\n\n=== Sega Genesis ===\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:70%\"\n! style=\"width:14em; text-align:left;\" | '''List of games'''\n! |\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n\n# Bonkers\n# Darksyne\n# Dyno Tennis\n# Ooze\n# Star Ball\n# Sidewinder\n# Daytona\n# 15 Puzzle\n# Sketch\n# Star Duel\n# Haunted Hill\n# Alfredo\n# The Cheetahmen\n# Skirmish\n# Depth Charge\n# Minds Eye\n# Alien Attack\n# Billy Bob\n# Sharks\n# Knockout\n# Intruder\n# Echo\n# Freeway\n# Mousetrap\n# Ninjaa\n# Slalom\n# Dauntless\n# Force One\n# Spidey\n# Appleseed\n# Skater\n# Sunday Drive\n# Star Evil\n# Air Command\n# Shootout\n# Bombs Away\n# Speed Boat\n# Dedant\n# G Fighter\n# Man At Arms\n# Norman\n# Armor Battle\n# Magic Bean\n# Apache\n# Paratrooper\n# Sky Avenger\n# Sharpshooter\n# Meteor\n# Black Hole\n# The Boss\n# First Game ([[Pong]])\n# Challenge\n\n|}\n[[Image:Spidey (Genesis).png|thumb|left|Gameplay of ''Spidey'' from the Genesis version (1993) of ''Action 52''.]]\nThe Sega Genesis version of ''Action 52'' features a largely different lineup of games, some with more effort put into design and fewer technical issues than the NES version.<ref name=\"Hardcore Gaming 101\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/action52/action52.htm |title=Action 52 - NES (1991) / Action 52 - Genesis (1993) / Cheetahmen 2 - NES (unreleased) |author =Jave |work=Hardcore Gaming 101 |accessdate=2010-10-04| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101010081350/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/action52/action52.htm| archivedate= 10 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Each game is color-coded on the main menu screen; \"Beginner\" games are green, \"Intermediate\" games are purple, \"Expert\" games are yellow, \"Challenge\" games are white, and multiplayer games are blue.<ref name=\"Hardcore Gaming 101\"/>\n\nSeveral new games were introduced in the Genesis version, a number of which share their names with games from the NES cartridge, but are different in terms of content. The Genesis ''Haunted Hills'', for instance, has a male protagonist and is set outside a [[haunted house]], while the NES ''Haunted Hills'' has a ''female'' protagonist and takes place ''inside'' a haunted house. A new rendition of ''The Cheetahmen'' was included, in which the Cheetahmen rescue captured cheetah cubs from Dr. Morbis and his minions.\n\nIn addition to the 52 games, the Genesis version features a Music Test mode and a \"Randomizer\" option. If selected from the main menu, the Randomizer will randomly choose and start one game from the 52 available on the cartridge. The fifty-second game, ''Challenge'', is an endurance test to see how long the player lasts in a random series of the highest levels of the other games.\n\n== Development ==\nLittle is known about Vince Perri, the creator of ''Action 52''. Perri claims to be a businessman from [[Miami]], [[Florida]] and the owner and founder of [[Active Enterprises]]. He also explains that the breakthrough came by accident: \"I happened to see my son playing an illegal product made in [[Taiwan]] that had 40 games on it. The whole neighborhood went crazy over it\", Perri said. \"I figured I'd do it legally. It's obvious when you see something like that, you know there's something there\".<ref name=mimhe>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20100506061008/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5487678_ITM Video Creator Plays 52 Games to Win]\". ''[[The Miami Herald]]''.</ref> In 1993, he showcased ''Action 52'' at the [[Consumer Electronics Show|International Winter Consumer Electronics Show]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAD91978A7B82C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Cartridge has 52 video games |date=1993-01-30 |newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the NES version, Perri raised $20 million from private backers in Europe, South America and Saudi Arabia. He and Ra\u00fal Gomila employed three college students (Mario Gonz\u00e1lez, Javier P\u00e9rez and Albert Hern\u00e1ndez) to do the game design, music, graphics and programming on an [[Atari ST]], with a three-month deadline and little playtesting or bug fixing done. Technical work was contracted out to Cronos Engineering, Inc., a [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] company that had done work for [[IBM]].<ref name=mimhe/> According to Gonz\u00e1lez, the game has been misrepresented as a \"scam\" in the gaming press; he clarifies that Perri never intended for the game to be a scam, at least at first, and believed it was a genuinely good business venture after seeing his neighborhood become entranced by his son's Taiwanese multicart. However, it was Perri's overconfidence and lack of gaming business savvy that led to the project's downfall, by hiring inexperienced programmers and giving them such a short deadline without knowing how long games typically took to make, and thinking such a poor-quality product would be able to make him rich via the ''Cheetahmen'' franchise.\n\n''Action 52'' has eight extra game templates, since the distributor had the carts come with 60 games by default, as well as many unused [[Tile-based video game|tiles]]; this has been confirmed in an interview with Gonz\u00e1lez. Also, according to Gonz\u00e1lez, the development team was flown to Sculptured Software to develop the game. While Mario does not remember the name of the game company, he recalls them both being based in Salt Lake City, Utah, and the company was developing an NES adaptation of ''[[The Empire Strikes Back|Star Wars V: The Empire Strikes Back]]''. This, along with the game using Sculptured Software's sound engine, proves that the game was developed at Sculptured Software, but not by Sculptured Software staff.\n\nSeveral of the songs from the NES version of ''Action 52'' were [[plagiarism|plagiarized]] from example tunes included in Activision's ''The Music Studio'' for the [[Atari ST]]. The games with plagiarized music include ''Fuzz Power'', ''Silver Sword'', ''French Baker'', ''Streemerz'', ''Time Warp Tickers'' and ''Ninja Assault''. Those songs were composed by [[Ed Bogas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/all_comments?v=PGQAhV8Ga1k|title=YouTube Video demonstrating matching songs from \"The Music Studio\" and \"Action 52\"|date=2009-02-12}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> Additionally, programmer Kevin Horton analyzed the music code of ''Action 52'' and found that it matched a music engine programmed by [[Sculptured Software]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nesdev.parodius.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7626|title=Post on NESDev forums by Kevin Horton|date=2011-04-05}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> featured in all of their NES games.\n\nThe Sega Genesis version, released two years later, was developed by [[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] on a [[Macintosh LC]] over the course of a year, under the direction of [[Jay Obernolte]].<ref name=\"Cheetahmen Corner\">{{cite web |url=http://cheetahmen.silius.net/obernolte.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423092507/http://cheetahmen.silius.net/obernolte.html |archivedate=2009-04-23 |title=Jay Obernolte Interview |year=2003 |author1=Harris, Andrew |author2=Allwein, Dave |work=Cheetahmen Corner |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref> This version contained far fewer glitches than the NES version, due to FarSight having experienced programmers and pressuring Active into playtesting the game before release. P\u00e9rez and Hern\u00e1ndez were again involved in the development of this version but Gonz\u00e1lez had departed from the team at this point to spend more time with his girlfriend, whom he eventually married. Music for this version was contracted out to Mark Steven Miller and Jason Scher of Nu Romantic Productions, which was composed within 48 hours. FarSight was also set to develop a version of ''Action 52'' for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], as well as another multicart titled ''Sports 5'', but Active Enterprises withdrew from the video game industry shortly thereafter, and no copies of either game are known to exist.\n\n== Prototypes ==\nThere are two know variations of \"Action 52\" prototypes known to have been produced. Prototype I (earliest) featured a blue colored circuit board in a clear cartridge with a sold blue colored label and did not have the \"Active Enterprises\" embossed on the rear. The second, prototype II, featured a black circuit board and clear, transparent, label; and did include the \"Active Enterprises\" embossing. It is unknown how many units of prototype II were made or still exit but is believed to be more than prototype I. The final, released, version of ''Action 52'' for the NES featured a clear cartridge with a green circuit board and transparent label with the \"Active Enterprises\" embossing.<ref name=\"The Video Game Museum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2010/06/17/whats-rarer-a-prototype-action-52-cart-or-a-person-who-met-vince-perri/ |title=What's Rarer: A Prototype Action 52 Cart or a Person Who Met Vince Perri? |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref> In 2010, a prototype I cartridge of ''Action 52'' surfaced, owned by movie and video games distributor Greg Pabich.<ref name=\"The Video Game Museum\"/> Originally, Vince Perri had proposed a deal with Pabich asking him if he would be interested in working for Active Enterprises as a business partner. At this time, Perri only had a few prototype cartridges and not the final product. For various reasons, Pabich turned down the offer, but not before leaving with one of the prototype I's in his possession, which was stored in his warehouse for over twenty years before it was \"rediscovered\".\n\nThe prototypes contain numerous differences from the final ''Action 52'' cartridges. They contain minor text differences for the game titles as well as different color backgrounds for the game selection menus. The final version contains the words \"Action 52\" in its header and copyright information in its footer. The prototypes simply contain section numbers in each menu screen's header. The code for ''Action 52'' appears to be heavily based upon the pirate multicart ''52 in 1''. This is evident from the menu template in the ''Action 52'' prototypes being identical to that of ''52 in 1''. However, the biggest difference between the prototypes and the final game is that the final version contains the game ''Cheetahmen'', whereas the prototypes do not. In its place is a completely different ''Cheetahmen'' game titled \"Action Gamer\" (presumably taken from the name of the main character, the Action Gamemaster, in Cheetahmen). Action Gamer features only two levels, one of which is incomplete.\n\nAfter Vince Perri insisted on the inclusion of his \"Cheetahmen\" in the final version of the game the \"Action Gamer\" levels were re-worked and renamed to ultimately become the 5th game on the cartridge titled \"Ooze\", the same title which, as was promoted, that if an individual player were to beat that title they would be entered to win a prize of US$104,000 ($52,000 cash & $52,000 scholarship).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2010/06/24/the-evolution-of-the-action-52/ |title=The Evolution of Action 52 |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref>\n\nOn November 11, 2011, Greg Pabich publicly released reproductions of ''Action Gamer'', calling it \"Cheetahmen: The Creation\". This was achieved by stripping the ROM data from one of the original prototype I cartridges and completing the game coding.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/cheetahmen/cheetahmen-ii-the-lost-levels |title=Cheetahmen Campaign |publisher=Greg Pabich}}</ref> This special package contains a sealed version of the game for collectors, an unsealed copy, a reproduction of the original ''Cheetahmen'' comic book, a ''Cheetahmen'' music CD, special edition T-shirts, and a poster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2011/10/21/cheetahmen-fever/ |title=Cheetahmen Fever! |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, one of the four original ''Action 52'' developers surfaced, presenting their original boxed ''Action 52'' NES prototype I cartridge, one of only two prototype I's known to exist. They have since created a blog documenting their part in the development of the ''Action 52'' NES cartridge.<ref name=\"Action52Prototype\">{{cite web|title=Action 52 Prototype |url=http://Action52Prototype.com |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130110142421/http://action52prototype.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt is noted that in 2018, Pabich acquired the prototype I owned by the developer #4 for a rumored five-figure price.\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section |date=October 2017}}\n{{Video game reviews\n | Allgame = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"allgamereview\">{{cite web |url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |title = Action 52 - Review| author = Miller, Skyler |publisher = [[AllGame]] |accessdate =October 20, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211102957/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |archivedate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe overall critical reception of ''Action 52'' has been overtly negative; AllGame editor Skyler Miller described the game as an \"unlicensed but legal multi-cart\" containing \"NES games of extremely poor quality\".<ref name=\"allgamereview\">{{cite web |url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |title = Action 52 - Review| author = Miller, Skyler |publisher = [[AllGame]] |accessdate =October 20, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211102957/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |archivedate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Video games|1990s}}\n* [[List of commercial failures in video gaming]]\n* [[List of video games notable for negative reception]]\n* ''[[Caltron 6 in 1]]''\n* ''[[Cassette 50]]''\n* ''[[Don't Buy This]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929190209/http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52text.htm List of all ''Action 52'' games] \u2014 A comprehensive website detailing all 52 of the games in the compilation.\n* [http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/active.html Active Enterprises exposed] \u2014 A website with information on both ''Action 52'' and Active Enterprises.\n* [http://www.cheetahmengames.com/index.html Cheetahmengames.com] \u2014 Official website of ''The Cheetahmen''.\n* [https://archive.is/20130116160715/http://www.action52prototype.com/ Action52Prototype.com] \u2014 Action 52 Developer #4's firsthand story of the development of ''Action 52'' and the rare ''Action 52'' prototype NES game cartridge.\n\n[[Category:Video games scored by Ed Bogas]]\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:Unauthorized video games]]\n[[Category:Video game compilations]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:North America-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Super Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:FarSight Studios games]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Unlicensed multicart video game compilation}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n|title          = Action 52\n|image          = Action 52 (NES) box art.jpg\n|caption        = NES cover art\n|developer      = [[Active Enterprises]] <small>(NES)</small><br>[[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] <small>(Genesis)</small>\n|publisher      = Active Enterprises\n|director       = Vince Perri<br />[[Jay Obernolte]] {{small|(Genesis)}}\n|producer       = Vince Perri<br />Raul Gomila<br />Jay Obernolte {{small|(Genesis)}}\n|designer       = Mario Gonzalez {{small|(NES)}}\n|programmer     = Albert Hernandez<br />Cronos Engineering, Inc.\n|artist         = Javier Perez\n|writer         = Mario Gonzalez {{small|(NES)}}\n|composer       = '''NES''':<br />Mario Gonzalez<br />Javier Perez<br />[[Ed Bogas]] {{small|(uncredited)}}<br />'''Genesis''':<br />Nu Romantic Productions (Mark Steven Miller and Jason Scher)\n|series         = \n|released       = '''NES'''<br><sup>'''[[North America|NA]]'''</sup> [[1991 in video gaming|1991]]<br>'''Sega Genesis'''<br><sup>'''[[North America|NA]]'''</sup> [[1993 in video gaming|1993]]<br>'''SNES'''<br><sup>Cancelled</sup>\n|genre          = Various\n|modes          = [[Single-player]] <br> [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n|platforms      = [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]] <br> [[Sega Genesis]]\n}}\n'''''Action 52''''' is an unlicensed [[multicart]] [[video game]] compilation developed by Active Enterprises for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], and [[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] for the [[Sega Genesis]]. The NES version was released in 1991, followed by the Genesis version in 1993. A  [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]] version was advertised in magazines, but never released. Active Enterprises was legally incorporated in the Bahamas, however, offices and development were located in Miami, Florida while the company's product warehousing was located in Orlando, Florida.\n\n''Action 52'' consists of 52 games that cover a variety of [[video game genre|genres]], with the most common being [[Shoot 'em up|scrolling shooter]]s and [[platform game|platformer]]s.<ref name=\"Action 52 for NES - MobyGames\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mobygames.com/game/action-52 |publisher=[[MobyGames]] |title=Action 52 for NES - MobyGames |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref> One of the more notable games is ''[[The Cheetahmen]]'', Active's attempt at creating a franchise similar to the [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]].\n\nThe NES version of ''Action 52'' became notorious among gamers for the poor quality and functionality of its games, and is often considered to be the [[List of video games notable for negative reception|worst game of all time]]. The Genesis version is widely considered superior, though still of subpar quality. Many [[Video game collecting|video game collectors]] value ''Action 52'' for its notoriety and rarity. It initially retailed for the comparatively high price of [[USD|US$]]199 ({{Inflation|US|199|1991|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gamespy.com/top10/december02/shame/index2.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414065846/http://archive.gamespy.com/top10/december02/shame/index2.shtml|archivedate=2009-04-14 |title=Top Ten Shameful Games |publisher=Archive.gamespy.com |date=2002-12-31 |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n\n===NES===\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:70%\"\n! style=\"width:14em; text-align:left;\" | '''List of games'''\n! |\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n\n# Fire Breathers\n# Star Evil\n# Illuminator\n# G-Force Fighters\n# Ooze\n# Silver Sword\n# Critical Bypass\n# Jupiter Scope\n# Alfredo (\"Alfred N the Fettuc\" on the title screen, widely known to be \"Alfredo and the Fettuccine\")\n# Operation Full-Moon\n# Dam Busters\n# Thrusters\n# Haunted Hill (\"Haunted Halls\" on the title screen, \"Haunted Halls of Wentworth\" in the manual)\n# Chill Out\n# Sharks\n# Megalonia\n# French Baker\n# Atmos Quake\n# Meong\n# Space Dreams\n# Streemerz (lacks its title on the title screen)\n# Spread Fire\n# Bubblegum Rosy (\"Bubblegum Rossie\" on the title screen)\n# Micro Mike (\"Micro-Mike\" on the title screen)\n# Underground\n# Rocket Jock (\"Rocket Jockey\" on the title screen)\n# Non Human\n# Cry Baby\n# Slashers\n# Crazy Shuffle\n# Fuzz Power\n# Shooting Gallery\n# Lollipops (\"Lollipop\" on the title screen)\n# Evil Empire\n# Sombreros\n# Storm Over the Desert\n# Mash Man\n# They Came (\"They Came...\" on the title screen)\n# Lazer League\n# Billy Bob (lacks its title on the title screen)\n# City of Doom\n# Bits and Pieces\n# Beeps and Blips\n# Manchester Beat\n# The Boss\n# Dedant\n# Hambo (\"Hambo's Adventures\" on the title screen)\n# Time Warp Tickers\n# Jigsaw\n# Ninja Assault\n# Robbie Robot (\"Robbie N the Robots\" on the title screen)\n# The Cheetahmen (\"Action Gamemaster\" on the title screen)\n\n|}\n[[File:Hauntedhills.png|thumb|left|Gameplay of ''Haunted Halls of Wentworth'' from the NES version (1991) of ''Action 52''.]]\nThe games on the NES version cover a variety of [[video game genre|genres]], the most common being [[shoot 'em up|vertical shooters]] set in outer space and [[platform game|platformers]].<ref name=\"Action 52 for NES - MobyGames\"/> The games have major [[glitch]]es, some of which cause them to freeze or crash due to programming flaws; there are also incomplete or endless levels, confusing design and unresponsive controls. In the manual, each game has a one-sentence description, with some being described as completely different games and others incorrectly described or categorized.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}\n\nThe \"featured\" game of ''Action 52'' was ''[[The Cheetahmen]]''. There were initial plans for a line of merchandise including action figures, T-shirts, a comic book series, and a television cartoon based on the characters (an advertisement for ''Cheetahmen'' action figures, displaying prototype sketches, was included in the aforementioned comic book).<ref name=\"Active Exposed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/active.html |title=Active Enterprises exposed |publisher=atarihq.com |accessdate=2009-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52stuff.htm |title=Action 52 - th' Stuff |publisher=Arkfullofsorrow.com |accessdate=2009-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110913045933/http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52stuff.htm |archivedate=2011-09-13 }}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> However, these plans quickly fell through as [[word of mouth]] and reviews mounted after the game's release.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nA [[Yeah! Woo!]] [[Break (music)|drum break]] that is sampled from [[Rob Base and DJ E-Z Rock|Rob Base]]'s song \"[[It Takes Two (Rob Base & DJ E-Z Rock song)|It Takes Two]]\" is used, only in the opening sequence of the NES version.<ref>{{Citation|title = Action 52 - Angry Video Game Nerd - Episode 90|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a4QBeADNM34&t=167|date = 2011-07-21|accessdate = 2016-02-21|last = Cinemassacre}}</ref>\n\nActive Enterprises advertised a competition in which anyone who could complete level 5 of ''Ooze'' would be entered into a prize drawing to win $104,000 ($52,000 cash, and a scholarship of the same value). The game was reported to crash on level 2, making this prize impossible to win<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.411mania.com/games/columns/67085/The-Hall-of-Shame-01.17.08:-Action-52.htm |title=411mania.com: Games - The Hall of Shame 01.17.08: Action 52 |date=2008-01-17 |author=Chiucchi, Vincent |publisher=411mania.com |accessdate=2009-11-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100506075008/http://www.411mania.com/games/columns/67085/The-Hall-of-Shame-01.17.08:-Action-52.htm |archivedate=2010-05-06 }}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> without the use of an emulator or an in-game exploit, rendering the contest a failure.\n\n=== Sega Genesis ===\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed\" border=\"0\" style=\"width:70%\"\n! style=\"width:14em; text-align:left;\" | '''List of games'''\n! |\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n\n# Bonkers\n# Darksyne\n# Dyno Tennis\n# Ooze\n# Star Ball\n# Sidewinder\n# Daytona\n# 15 Puzzle\n# Sketch\n# Star Duel\n# Haunted Hill\n# Alfredo\n# The Cheetahmen\n# Skirmish\n# Depth Charge\n# Minds Eye\n# Alien Attack\n# Billy Bob\n# Sharks\n# Knockout\n# Intruder\n# Echo\n# Freeway\n# Mousetrap\n# Ninjaa\n# Slalom\n# Dauntless\n# Force One\n# Spidey\n# Appleseed\n# Skater\n# Sunday Drive\n# Star Evil\n# Air Command\n# Shootout\n# Bombs Away\n# Speed Boat\n# Dedant\n# G Fighter\n# Man At Arms\n# Norman\n# Armor Battle\n# Magic Bean\n# Apache\n# Paratrooper\n# Sky Avenger\n# Sharpshooter\n# Meteor\n# Black Hole\n# The Boss\n# First Game ([[Pong]])\n# Challenge\n\n|}\n[[Image:Spidey (Genesis).png|thumb|left|Gameplay of ''Spidey'' from the Genesis version (1993) of ''Action 52''.]]\nThe Sega Genesis version of ''Action 52'' features a largely different lineup of games, some with more effort put into design and fewer technical issues than the NES version.<ref name=\"Hardcore Gaming 101\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/action52/action52.htm |title=Action 52 - NES (1991) / Action 52 - Genesis (1993) / Cheetahmen 2 - NES (unreleased) |author =Jave |work=Hardcore Gaming 101 |accessdate=2010-10-04| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101010081350/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/action52/action52.htm| archivedate= 10 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Each game is color-coded on the main menu screen; \"Beginner\" games are green, \"Intermediate\" games are purple, \"Expert\" games are yellow, \"Challenge\" games are white, and multiplayer games are blue.<ref name=\"Hardcore Gaming 101\"/>\n\nSeveral new games were introduced in the Genesis version, a number of which share their names with games from the NES cartridge, but are different in terms of content. The Genesis ''Haunted Hills'', for instance, has a male protagonist and is set outside a [[haunted house]], while the NES ''Haunted Hills'' has a ''female'' protagonist and takes place ''inside'' a haunted house. A new rendition of ''The Cheetahmen'' was included, in which the Cheetahmen rescue captured cheetah cubs from Dr. Morbis and his minions.\n\nIn addition to the 52 games, the Genesis version features a Music Test mode and a \"Randomizer\" option. If selected from the main menu, the Randomizer will randomly choose and start one game from the 52 available on the cartridge. The fifty-second game, ''Challenge'', is an endurance test to see how long the player lasts in a random series of the highest levels of the other games.\n\n== Development ==\nLittle is known about Vince Perri, the creator of ''Action 52''. Perri claims to be a businessman from [[Miami]], [[Florida]] and the owner and founder of [[Active Enterprises]]. He also explains that the breakthrough came by accident: \"I happened to see my son playing an illegal product made in [[Taiwan]] that had 40 games on it. The whole neighborhood went crazy over it\", Perri said. \"I figured I'd do it legally. It's obvious when you see something like that, you know there's something there\".<ref name=mimhe>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20100506061008/http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-5487678_ITM Video Creator Plays 52 Games to Win]\". ''[[The Miami Herald]]''.</ref> In 1993, he showcased ''Action 52'' at the [[Consumer Electronics Show|International Winter Consumer Electronics Show]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAD91978A7B82C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Cartridge has 52 video games |date=1993-01-30 |newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the NES version, Perri raised $20 million from private backers in Europe, South America and Saudi Arabia. He and Ra\u00fal Gomila employed three college students (Mario Gonz\u00e1lez, Javier P\u00e9rez and Albert Hern\u00e1ndez) to do the game design, music, graphics and programming on an [[Atari ST]], with a three-month deadline and little playtesting or bug fixing done. Technical work was contracted out to Cronos Engineering, Inc., a [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] company that had done work for [[IBM]].<ref name=mimhe/> According to Gonz\u00e1lez, the game has been misrepresented as a \"scam\" in the gaming press; he clarifies that Perri never intended for the game to be a scam, at least at first, and believed it was a genuinely good business venture after seeing his neighborhood become entranced by his son's Taiwanese multicart. However, it was Perri's overconfidence and lack of gaming business savvy that led to the project's downfall, by hiring inexperienced programmers and giving them such a short deadline without knowing how long games typically took to make, and thinking such a poor-quality product would be able to make him rich via the ''Cheetahmen'' franchise.\n\n''Action 52'' has eight extra game templates, since the distributor had the carts come with 60 games by default, as well as many unused [[Tile-based video game|tiles]]; this has been confirmed in an interview with Gonz\u00e1lez. Also, according to Gonz\u00e1lez, the development team was flown to Sculptured Software to develop the game. While Mario does not remember the name of the game company, he recalls them both being based in Salt Lake City, Utah, and the company was developing an NES adaptation of ''[[The Empire Strikes Back|Star Wars V: The Empire Strikes Back]]''. This, along with the game using Sculptured Software's sound engine, proves that the game was developed at Sculptured Software, but not by Sculptured Software staff.\n\nSeveral of the songs from the NES version of ''Action 52'' were [[plagiarism|plagiarized]] from example tunes included in Activision's ''The Music Studio'' for the [[Atari ST]]. The games with plagiarized music include ''Fuzz Power'', ''Silver Sword'', ''French Baker'', ''Streemerz'', ''Time Warp Tickers'' and ''Ninja Assault''. Those songs were composed by [[Ed Bogas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/all_comments?v=PGQAhV8Ga1k|title=YouTube Video demonstrating matching songs from \"The Music Studio\" and \"Action 52\"|date=2009-02-12}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> Additionally, programmer Kevin Horton analyzed the music code of ''Action 52'' and found that it matched a music engine programmed by [[Sculptured Software]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nesdev.parodius.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7626|title=Post on NESDev forums by Kevin Horton|date=2011-04-05}}{{unreliable source?|date=June 2014}}</ref> featured in all of their NES games.\n\nThe Sega Genesis version, released two years later, was developed by [[FarSight Studios|FarSight Technologies]] on a [[Macintosh LC]] over the course of a year, under the direction of [[Jay Obernolte]].<ref name=\"Cheetahmen Corner\">{{cite web |url=http://cheetahmen.silius.net/obernolte.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423092507/http://cheetahmen.silius.net/obernolte.html |archivedate=2009-04-23 |title=Jay Obernolte Interview |year=2003 |author1=Harris, Andrew |author2=Allwein, Dave |work=Cheetahmen Corner |accessdate=2010-10-04}}</ref> This version contained far fewer glitches than the NES version, due to FarSight having experienced programmers and pressuring Active into playtesting the game before release. P\u00e9rez and Hern\u00e1ndez were again involved in the development of this version but Gonz\u00e1lez had departed from the team at this point to spend more time with his girlfriend, whom he eventually married. Music for this version was contracted out to Mark Steven Miller and Jason Scher of Nu Romantic Productions, which was composed within 48 hours. FarSight was also set to develop a version of ''Action 52'' for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], as well as another multicart titled ''Sports 5'', but Active Enterprises withdrew from the video game industry shortly thereafter, and no copies of either game are known to exist.\n\n== Prototypes ==\nThere are two know variations of \"Action 52\" prototypes known to have been produced. Prototype I (earliest) featured a blue colored circuit board in a clear cartridge with a sold blue colored label and did not have the \"Active Enterprises\" embossed on the rear. The second, prototype II, featured a black circuit board and clear, transparent, label; and did include the \"Active Enterprises\" embossing. It is unknown how many units of prototype II were made or still exit but is believed to be more than prototype I. The final, released, version of ''Action 52'' for the NES featured a clear cartridge with a green circuit board and transparent label with the \"Active Enterprises\" embossing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2010/06/17/whats-rarer-a-prototype-action-52-cart-or-a-person-who-met-vince-perri/ |title=What's Rarer: A Prototype Action 52 Cart or a Person Who Met Vince Perri? |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref> In 2010, a prototype I cartridge of ''Action 52'' surfaced, owned by movie and video games distributor Greg Pabich.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2010/06/17/whats-rarer-a-prototype-action-52-cart-or-a-person-who-met-vince-perri/ |title=What's Rarer: A Prototype Action 52 Cart or a Person Who Met Vince Perri? |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref> Originally, Vince Perri had proposed a deal with Pabich asking him if he would be interested in working for Active Enterprises as a business partner. At this time, Perri only had a few prototype cartridges and not the final product. For various reasons, Pabich turned down the offer, but not before leaving with one of the prototype I's in his possession, which was stored in his warehouse for over twenty years before it was \"rediscovered\".\n\nThe prototypes contain numerous differences from the final ''Action 52'' cartridges. They contain minor text differences for the game titles as well as different color backgrounds for the game selection menus. The final version contains the words \"Action 52\" in its header and copyright information in its footer. The prototypes simply contain section numbers in each menu screen's header. The code for ''Action 52'' appears to be heavily based upon the pirate multicart ''52 in 1''. This is evident from the menu template in the ''Action 52'' prototypes being identical to that of ''52 in 1''. However, the biggest difference between the prototypes and the final game is that the final version contains the game ''Cheetahmen'', whereas the prototypes do not. In its place is a completely different ''Cheetahmen'' game titled \"Action Gamer\" (presumably taken from the name of the main character, the Action Gamemaster, in Cheetahmen). Action Gamer features only two levels, one of which is incomplete. \n\nAfter Vince Perri insisted on the inclusion of his \"Cheetahmen\" in the final version of the game the \"Action Gamer\" levels were re-worked and re-named to ultimately become the 5th game on the cartridge titled \"Ooze\", the same title which, as was promoted, that if an individual player were to beat that title they would be entered to win a prize of $104,000 USD ($52,000 cash & $52,000 scholarship). <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2010/06/24/the-evolution-of-the-action-52/ |title=The Evolution of Action 52 |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref>\n\nOn November 11, 2011, Greg Pabich publicly released reproductions of ''Action Gamer'', calling it \"Cheetahmen: The Creation\". This was achieved by stripping the ROM data from one of the original prototype I cartridges and completing the game coding. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/cheetahmen/cheetahmen-ii-the-lost-levels |title=Cheetahmen Campaign |publisher=Greg Pabich}}</ref> This special package contains a sealed version of the game for collectors, an unsealed copy, a reproduction of the original ''Cheetahmen'' comic book, a ''Cheetahmen'' music CD, special edition T-shirts, and a poster.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamemuseum.com/2011/10/21/cheetahmen-fever/ |title=Cheetahmen Fever! |publisher=The Video Game Museum}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, one of the four original ''Action 52'' developers surfaced, presenting their original boxed ''Action 52'' NES prototype I cartridge, one of only two prototype I's known to exist. They have since created a blog documenting their part in the development of the ''Action 52'' NES cartridge.<ref name=\"Action52Prototype\">{{cite web|title=Action 52 Prototype |url=http://Action52Prototype.com |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130110142421/http://action52prototype.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt is noted that in 2018, Pabich acquired the prototype I owned by the developer #4 for a rumored five-figure price.\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section |date=October 2017}}\n{{Video game reviews\n | Allgame = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=\"allgamereview\">{{cite web |url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |title = Action 52 - Review| author = Miller, Skyler |publisher = [[AllGame]] |accessdate =October 20, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211102957/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |archivedate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe overall critical reception of ''Action 52'' has been overtly negative; AllGame editor Skyler Miller described the game as an \"unlicensed but legal multi-cart\" containing \"NES games of extremely poor quality\".<ref name=\"allgamereview\">{{cite web |url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |title = Action 52 - Review| author = Miller, Skyler |publisher = [[AllGame]] |accessdate =October 20, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211102957/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=22137&tab=review |archivedate=December 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Video games|1990s}}\n* [[List of commercial failures in video gaming]]\n* [[List of video games notable for negative reception]]\n* ''[[Caltron 6 in 1]]''\n* ''[[Cassette 50]]''\n* ''[[Don't Buy This]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929190209/http://www.arkfullofsorrow.com/a52text.htm List of all ''Action 52'' games] \u2014 A comprehensive website detailing all 52 of the games in the compilation.\n* [http://www.atarihq.com/tsr/special/active.html Active Enterprises exposed] \u2014 A website with information on both ''Action 52'' and Active Enterprises.\n* [http://www.cheetahmengames.com/index.html Cheetahmengames.com] \u2014 Official website of ''The Cheetahmen''.\n* [https://archive.is/20130116160715/http://www.action52prototype.com/ Action52Prototype.com] \u2014 Action 52 Developer #4's firsthand story of the development of ''Action 52'' and the rare ''Action 52'' prototype NES game cartridge.\n\n[[Category:Video games scored by Ed Bogas]]\n[[Category:1991 video games]]\n[[Category:Unauthorized video games]]\n[[Category:Video game compilations]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:North America-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Super Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:FarSight Studios games]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrototypes:clean up,typo(s) fixed: $104,000 USD \u2192  US$104,000, re-named \u2192 renamed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_52"}
{"title_page": "Sheeva", "text_new": "{{about|the ''Mortal Kombat'' character|the Hindu aspect of God|Shiva}}\n{{Infobox video game character\n|color=#979797\n|name=Sheeva\n|image=SheevaMK2011.png\n|caption=Sheeva in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' (2011)\n|series=[[Mortal Kombat]]\n|firstgame=''[[Mortal Kombat 3]]'' (1995)\n|creator=[[John Tobias]]\n|designer = John Tobias (early games)<br>Atomhawk Design (''MK2011'')<br>Lynell Forestall (''MK:DotR'')<br>Jennifer L. Parsons (''Annihilation'')\n|motion_actor=Lorrisa Julianus (''MK 2011'')\n| portrayer = [[Marjean Holden]]\n|voice=[[Dawnn Lewis]] (''DotR'') <br> [[Lani Minella]] (''MK 2011'') <br> [[Vanessa Marshall]] (''MK11'')\n|origin=Outworld\n|lbl21 = Fighting styles\n|data21=Kuatan (''MK:A'')\n|weapon=Shokan Daggers (''MK:A'')\n}}\n\n'''Sheeva''' is a [[fictional character]] in the ''[[Mortal Kombat (series)|Mortal Kombat]]'' fighting game series created by [[Ed Boon]] and [[John Tobias]]. Making her first appearance in ''[[Mortal Kombat 3]]'' (1995), she is of the multilimbed Shokan species from the otherworldly realm of Outworld, like [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]] and [[Kintaro (Mortal Kombat character)|Kintaro]]. She has served as the personal protector of Outworld emperor [[Shao Kahn]]'s queen, [[Sindel]], while harboring a bitter hatred for [[Motaro]], who is of the Shokan's sworn enemies, the Centaurians. In the 2011 [[Mortal Kombat (2011 game)|reboot]], her role in the storyline is that of Kahn's [[bodyguard]] and [[Prison officer|jailer]], holding [[Sonya Blade]] and [[Kitana]] captive on separate occasions.\n\nCreated as a stop motion-animated figurine like Goro and Kintaro, Sheeva was added into the ''MK'' (Mortal Kombat) series due to fan requests for a playable version of Goro. However, out of all the characters from the first generation of games, she has featured the least in the overall series continuity to date, only appearing as a playable in two additional titles after ''MK3'' and its upgrades (''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'' and ''[[Mortal Kombat Trilogy]]'') in addition to small roles in alternative ''Mortal Kombat''-related media, while appearing on no official merchandise. Reception to the character has been mixed in terms of her presence in the series and her finishing moves.\n\nHer name comes from the one true almighty [[Shiva]], the four-handed deity who is the one true god; the only difference is that Shiva is male and obviously the almighty and non comparable with anyone one in with world... Har Har Mahadev...\n\n==Appearances==\n===In video games===\nSheeva belongs to the ancient race of the Shokan, described as a subterranean people living in Outworld. Like all of her race, she possesses a tall, muscular build, red eyes, four arms with three fingers on each totaling 12 fingers, and two toes on each foot, however special to her only is the horns on her head. When [[Shao Kahn]] resurrected Sindel as the first step in his invasion of earth, he appointed Sheeva to be her personal protector. Sheeva became distrustful, however, when Kahn appointed the centaur [[Motaro]] to lead his Extermination Squads into battle. She saw this as an insult, as the Shokan and Centaurs have long been mortal enemies. She served the emperor in Earthrealm, but when she returned to Outworld, she was shocked to learn that Shao Kahn had betrayed the Shokans, and had launched an offensive against them. She joins her fellow Shokans in fighting Kahn\u2019s warriors. The Shokans are far outnumbered, and cannot hope to win, but when Shao Kahn is defeated by Earth\u2019s warriors and recalls his troops from all fronts, Sheeva takes this opportunity to get revenge on her nemesis, Motaro. Days later, she learns that Motaro has nursed his Earthrealm ally, Kano, back to health. Although Motaro had rescued Kano, it was merely to imprison him so he could later face the wrath of Shao Kahn for his failure to defeat Sonya. He gets imprisoned. Some time later, Sheeva arrives to the palace. The Shokan warrior kills Motaro outside of Kano's cell. She was on her way to assassinate Shao Kahn as well when Kano offered his assistance if Sheeva let him out of his cage. Kano and Sheeva proceeded to the throne room of Shao Kahn. When they arrived at the door, Kano suggested that he go in first to distract the Emperor. Kano would give the signal for Sheeva to enter and slay the preoccupied Shao Kahn. But Kano betrayed Sheeva and informed Shao Kahn of her assassination plot. When Kano called her in, Shao Kahn thrust a sword through her chest from behind.\n\nIn ''[[Mortal Kombat: Armageddon]]'' it is possible that Sheeva has escaped from the Netherealm some how, this is unknown how though as it was never confirmed. In ''Armegeddon's'' Konquest mode, Sheeva is seen in the Netherealm along with [[Kintaro (Mortal Kombat)|Kintaro]], [[Havik]], and a legion of demons all apparently working in an attempt to overthrow [[Shinnok]]'s rule at his spire. However, Shinnok later reveals that they were only apparitions created as a test for [[Taven]], thus making it clear that it was not the real Sheeva. In Sheeva's ''Armageddon'' ending, she defeats [[Blaze (Mortal Kombat)|Blaze]] and is met by the Elder Gods. She becomes the Goddess of Destruction, destroying realms using a Kamidogu; she then recreates the realms however she sees fit, but exactly what they are remade into is never revealed.<ref name=\"MKAend\">[http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mka/sheeva/ Sheeva's ''Armageddon'' info] at Mortal Kombat Warehouse.</ref>\n\nSheeva also appears in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat 2011]]''. In the Story Mode, she is Shao Kahn's bodyguard, also serving as a jailer when Sonya and later Kitana are held captive, and must be fought several times by the characters the Story Mode focuses on. She is last seen defeated by Kabal in the streets of New York City after he escapes from Outworld. Despite this, she does not appear in ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]''.  In her noncanonical ending, she goes to Raiden for help in protecting her people from the loyal followers of Shao Kahn, fearing that the Shokan will be targets over her defeat of the emperor.  The Elder God shows her mercy and relocates her and her people to Earthrealm, where they make the continent of [[Australia]] their new home, and it is there that Sheeva becomes their new ruler.\n\nSheeva returns as an NPC ally of the heroes in ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''. She is first seen when the past iteration of Kitana tries to convince her to aid Kotal Kahn against the returned Shao Kahn. Sheeva, however, is hesitant to get involved unless there is a real chance of victory. To that end, she states that she will join only if Baraka and his Tarkatans can be persuaded to join as well. After Kitana achieves this, Sheeva accompanies her in storming the Koliseum to prevent Kotal's execution. Later, Sheeva becomes one of Kitana's primary lieutenants after  the now-crippled Kotal appoints her the new Kahn. To that end, she joins the alliance for the final battle against Kronika's army in the Netherrealm, holding off Kronika's remaining armies while Liu Kang, Kung Lao, and Kitana proceed to Kronika's time chamber.\n\n====Design and gameplay====\nSheeva, whose name was derived from [[Shiva]], a Hindu deity of destruction, was introduced into the series due to fan requests for a playable version of [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]].<ref name=\"MKABioCard\">Sheeva's Bio Card. ''Mortal Kombat: Armageddon Premium Edition'' Bonus Disc, Midway Games, 2006.</ref> She was not included among the selectable fighters in the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] and [[Sega Genesis]] version of ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'' due to memory constraints, though she appeared as a glitch character in the SNES version of ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]''.  Sheeva's blood was green in ''MK3'' through ''[[Mortal Kombat Trilogy]]'' (although if this was done simply because she was a Shokan, it made little sense, seeing as both Goro and Kintaro had red blood in previous games). She was the first character to have this particular blood color (not counting the censored Japanese version of ''[[Mortal Kombat II]]'', in which all characters had green blood). Her blood color was changed to red in ''Armageddon''.\n\nUntil the release of ''MK: Armageddon'', Sheeva had not appeared as a playable character since ''MK Trilogy'', nor did she have had any substantial cameos; only her corpse was found in the Netherealm in ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deception]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Konquest mode and is seen running through the graveyard in the game's Krypt, in which almost all ''MK'' characters had cameos. Her fate after ''MK Trilogy'' was revealed in the text from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Konquest mode. In ''Armageddon'''s arcade mode, Sheeva sometimes appeared as a sub-boss before the final fight with Blaze. She is the only Shokan character that can perform aerial combos, and the only Shokan character that can be thrown by normal characters in the game. While she has Goro's offensive moves, she is female so that she would be smaller in size and therefore the same height as the other fighters.\n\n===In other media===\nSheeva appears in ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]],'' played by [[Marjean Holden]]. The [[shooting script]] included a lengthy fight scene with [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]] that was omitted during filming; instead, she was simply crushed by a falling cage in Kahn's throne room. Her only action sequence was a brief quarrel with Motaro, though the film did acknowledge that she was once Sindel's personal protector. In a 2001 interview with fansite Total Mortal Kombat, Holden expressed her displeasure at the filmmakers' treatment of her character. In the [[shooting script]] and novelization, Sheeva met her demise in an extensive fight scene with newly mortal Raiden, but the scene was never filmed and her screen time was scant in the finished print, with Raiden instead fighting two Raptors and Sheeva's death simply coming from a falling cage. \"Here was a character, that was one of the most popular [in] the video game...and they killed her without even so much as a fight! Something I was not happy about at all. That was one of the reasons I wanted to do the role, was for the sheer fact that there were really great fights in the movie for this character, and they all got cut out.\"<ref name=\"tmk\">[http://www.totalmortalkombat.com/cast/interviews/index.php?action=interview&interview_id=2 Interview with: Marjean Holden] - Total Mortal Kombat, 2/4/01</ref>\n\nSheeva has a small role in the animated series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'', in which she harbored a long-standing animosity toward Raiden. She was voiced by [[Dawnn Lewis]].\n\nIn the 2015 ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]'' prequel comic miniseries produced by [[DC Comics]], Sheeva is crowned by Kintaro as the current leader of the Shokan in a peaceful treaty with Kotal Kahn, following the death of previous rule King Gorbak. Sheeva mourned Kintaro's death when a possessed [[Sonya Blade]] killed him in battle.\n\n==Reception==\nReception of the character has been mixed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheevafanclub.wordpress.com/|title=Sheeva Fan Club|website=Sheeva Fan Club|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> ''SuperGamePower'' gave her their anti-awards for the ugliest female character of both 1996 and 1997.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1997|title=Os melhores do videogame|url=|journal=SuperGamePower|volume=38|pages=15|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1998|title=II Oscar do videogame|url=|journal=SuperGamePowe|volume=50|pages=11|via=}}</ref> In 2011, [[Wirtualna Polska]] featured her among the top ten villainesses in gaming, as \"an attraction for connoisseurs of unusual beauty and even more unusual quantities of the various parts of the body.\"<ref>[http://gry.wp.pl/galeria/10-najseksowniejszych-negatywnych-bohaterek,179679/10.html Sheeva \u2013 Mortal Kombat - 10 najseksowniejszych negatywnych bohaterek - Imperium gier - WP.PL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321150440/http://gry.wp.pl/galeria/10-najseksowniejszych-negatywnych-bohaterek,179679/10.html |date=2012-03-21 }} {{in lang|pl}}</ref> In 2012, [[UGO.com]] ranked her as the 28th top ''Mortal Kombat'' character.<ref>{{cite web |author=UGO Team |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters-sheeva |title=Sheeva - Top 50 Mortal Kombat Characters |publisher=UGO.com |date=2012-02-28 |accessdate=2012-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316074322/http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters-sheeva |archivedate=2013-03-16 }}</ref> Sheeva ranked 36th on a 2013 fan poll hosted by Dorkly that rated the entire series roster. Den of Geek ranked Sheeva 34th in their 2015 rating of the franchises 64 characters. However, ''[[Game Informer]]'' listed her as one of the characters they did not want for ''MK2011'', stating that \"despite a somewhat cool ground-pound move, she was an addition to the series that never really served a purpose or did anything particularly noteworthy.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ulrich |first=Tyler |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2010/06/21/who-we-want-and-dont-want-in-the-new-mortal-kombat.aspx?PostPageIndex=2&PageIndex=6 |title=Who We Want (And Don\u2019t Want) In The New Mortal Kombat - Features |publisher=www.GameInformer.com |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> GamePlayBook ranked Sheeva fifth on their top 10 worst characters in the series. She was ranked as seventh goofiest ''Mortal Kombat'' character by [[Topless Robot]] in 2011.<ref name=goofy>{{cite web|url=http://www.toplessrobot.com/2011/04/8_mortal_kombat_characters_that_are_goofy_even_by.php |title=8 Mortal Kombat Characters That Are Goofy Even by Mortal Kombat Standards |publisher=Topless Robot |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n\nSheeva was featured in several lists of the best, and sometimes worst, finishing moves in the ''Mortal Kombat'' series by various publications. In 1996, her \"Skin Rip\" move received the most votes for favorite ''Mortal Kombat 3'' finishing move from ''[[GamePro]]'' readers.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=Reader Report|journal=[[GamePro]]|issue=91|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=April 1996|page=13}}</ref> In 2010, [[IGN]] ranked her \"Manly Forearms\" from ''MK3'' as the third best Fatality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ps3.ign.com/articles/113/1137436p1.html |title=IGN's Unofficial Top 10 List of the Best Mortal Kombat Fatalities - PS3 Feature at IGN |publisher=Uk.ps3.ign.com |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>  In 2011, she placed third on the lists of both the best (\"Skin Rip\" in ''MK3'') and the worst (\"Jackhammer\" in ''MK3'') Fatalities by GameRant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/top-10-best-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-75792/all/1/ |title=Top 10 Best Mortal Kombat Fatalities |publisher=Game Rant |date= |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/worst-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-79624/all/1/ |title=Top Ten Worst 'Mortal Kombat' Fatalities |publisher=Game Rant |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref> In 2012, [[GameFront]] ranked her \"Stripped Down\" Fatality from ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat 2011]]'' as the third best in the series,<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Gold |url=http://www.gamefront.com/mortal-kombats-10-best-fatalities/ |title=Mortal Kombat\u2019s 10 Best Fatalities |publisher=GameFront |date=2011-04-20 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref> while her other Fatality was also ranked as the ninth best in this game by ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nathan Spicer |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/04/best-fatalities-from-mortal-kombat-1-and-9.html |title=The 17 Best Fatalities from Mortal Kombat 1 & 9 :: Blogs :: List of the Day :: Paste |publisher=Pastemagazine.com |date=2011-04-23 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mortal Kombat series}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by John Tobias]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Female characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional bodyguards in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional hybrid life forms]]\n[[Category:Mortal Kombat characters]]\n[[Category:Video game antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in film]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in television]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1995]]\n\n[[fr:Sheeva]]\n[[pt:Sheeva]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the ''Mortal Kombat'' character|the Hindu aspect of God|Shiva}}\n{{Infobox video game character\n|color=#979797\n|name=Sheeva\n|image=SheevaMK2011.png\n|caption=Sheeva in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' (2011)\n|series=[[Mortal Kombat]]\n|firstgame=''[[Mortal Kombat 3]]'' (1995)\n|creator=[[John Tobias]]\n|designer = John Tobias (early games)<br>Atomhawk Design (''MK2011'')<br>Lynell Forestall (''MK:DotR'')<br>Jennifer L. Parsons (''Annihilation'')\n|motion_actor=Lorrisa Julianus (''MK 2011'')\n| portrayer = [[Marjean Holden]]\n|voice=[[Dawnn Lewis]] (''DotR'') <br> [[Lani Minella]] (''MK 2011'') <br> [[Vanessa Marshall]] (''MK11'')\n|origin=Outworld\n|lbl21 = Fighting styles\n|data21=Kuatan (''MK:A'')\n|weapon=Shokan Daggers (''MK:A'')\n}}\n\n'''Sheeva''' is a [[fictional character]] in the ''[[Mortal Kombat (series)|Mortal Kombat]]'' fighting game series created by [[Ed Boon]] and [[John Tobias]]. Making her first appearance in ''[[Mortal Kombat 3]]'' (1995), she is of the multilimbed Shokan species from the otherworldly realm of Outworld, like [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]] and [[Kintaro (Mortal Kombat character)|Kintaro]]. She has served as the personal protector of Outworld emperor [[Shao Kahn]]'s queen, [[Sindel]], while harboring a bitter hatred for [[Motaro]], who is of the Shokan's sworn enemies, the Centaurians. In the 2011 [[Mortal Kombat (2011 game)|reboot]], her role in the storyline is that of Kahn's [[bodyguard]] and [[Prison officer|jailer]], holding [[Sonya Blade]] and [[Kitana]] captive on separate occasions.\n\nCreated as a stop motion-animated figurine like Goro and Kintaro, Sheeva was added into the ''MK'' (Mortal Kombat) series due to fan requests for a playable version of Goro. However, out of all the characters from the first generation of games, she has featured the least in the overall series continuity to date, only appearing as a playable in two additional titles after ''MK3'' and its upgrades (''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'' and ''[[Mortal Kombat Trilogy]]'') in addition to small roles in alternative ''Mortal Kombat''-related media, while appearing on no official merchandise. Reception to the character has been mixed in terms of her presence in the series and her finishing moves.\n\nHer name comes from [[Shiva]], the four-handed Indian deity; the only difference is that Shiva is male.\n\n==Appearances==\n===In video games===\nSheeva belongs to the ancient race of the Shokan, described as a subterranean people living in Outworld. Like all of her race, she possesses a tall, muscular build, red eyes, four arms with three fingers on each totaling 12 fingers, and two toes on each foot, however special to her only is the horns on her head. When [[Shao Kahn]] resurrected Sindel as the first step in his invasion of earth, he appointed Sheeva to be her personal protector. Sheeva became distrustful, however, when Kahn appointed the centaur [[Motaro]] to lead his Extermination Squads into battle. She saw this as an insult, as the Shokan and Centaurs have long been mortal enemies. She served the emperor in Earthrealm, but when she returned to Outworld, she was shocked to learn that Shao Kahn had betrayed the Shokans, and had launched an offensive against them. She joins her fellow Shokans in fighting Kahn\u2019s warriors. The Shokans are far outnumbered, and cannot hope to win, but when Shao Kahn is defeated by Earth\u2019s warriors and recalls his troops from all fronts, Sheeva takes this opportunity to get revenge on her nemesis, Motaro. Days later, she learns that Motaro has nursed his Earthrealm ally, Kano, back to health. Although Motaro had rescued Kano, it was merely to imprison him so he could later face the wrath of Shao Kahn for his failure to defeat Sonya. He gets imprisoned. Some time later, Sheeva arrives to the palace. The Shokan warrior kills Motaro outside of Kano's cell. She was on her way to assassinate Shao Kahn as well when Kano offered his assistance if Sheeva let him out of his cage. Kano and Sheeva proceeded to the throne room of Shao Kahn. When they arrived at the door, Kano suggested that he go in first to distract the Emperor. Kano would give the signal for Sheeva to enter and slay the preoccupied Shao Kahn. But Kano betrayed Sheeva and informed Shao Kahn of her assassination plot. When Kano called her in, Shao Kahn thrust a sword through her chest from behind.\n\nIn ''[[Mortal Kombat: Armageddon]]'' it is possible that Sheeva has escaped from the Netherealm some how, this is unknown how though as it was never confirmed. In ''Armegeddon's'' Konquest mode, Sheeva is seen in the Netherealm along with [[Kintaro (Mortal Kombat)|Kintaro]], [[Havik]], and a legion of demons all apparently working in an attempt to overthrow [[Shinnok]]'s rule at his spire. However, Shinnok later reveals that they were only apparitions created as a test for [[Taven]], thus making it clear that it was not the real Sheeva. In Sheeva's ''Armageddon'' ending, she defeats [[Blaze (Mortal Kombat)|Blaze]] and is met by the Elder Gods. She becomes the Goddess of Destruction, destroying realms using a Kamidogu; she then recreates the realms however she sees fit, but exactly what they are remade into is never revealed.<ref name=\"MKAend\">[http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mka/sheeva/ Sheeva's ''Armageddon'' info] at Mortal Kombat Warehouse.</ref>\n\nSheeva also appears in ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat 2011]]''. In the Story Mode, she is Shao Kahn's bodyguard, also serving as a jailer when Sonya and later Kitana are held captive, and must be fought several times by the characters the Story Mode focuses on. She is last seen defeated by Kabal in the streets of New York City after he escapes from Outworld. Despite this, she does not appear in ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]''.  In her noncanonical ending, she goes to Raiden for help in protecting her people from the loyal followers of Shao Kahn, fearing that the Shokan will be targets over her defeat of the emperor.  The Elder God shows her mercy and relocates her and her people to Earthrealm, where they make the continent of [[Australia]] their new home, and it is there that Sheeva becomes their new ruler.\n\nSheeva returns as an NPC ally of the heroes in ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]''. She is first seen when the past iteration of Kitana tries to convince her to aid Kotal Kahn against the returned Shao Kahn. Sheeva, however, is hesitant to get involved unless there is a real chance of victory. To that end, she states that she will join only if Baraka and his Tarkatans can be persuaded to join as well. After Kitana achieves this, Sheeva accompanies her in storming the Koliseum to prevent Kotal's execution. Later, Sheeva becomes one of Kitana's primary lieutenants after  the now-crippled Kotal appoints her the new Kahn. To that end, she joins the alliance for the final battle against Kronika's army in the Netherrealm, holding off Kronika's remaining armies while Liu Kang, Kung Lao, and Kitana proceed to Kronika's time chamber.\n\n====Design and gameplay====\nSheeva, whose name was derived from [[Shiva]], a Hindu deity of destruction, was introduced into the series due to fan requests for a playable version of [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]].<ref name=\"MKABioCard\">Sheeva's Bio Card. ''Mortal Kombat: Armageddon Premium Edition'' Bonus Disc, Midway Games, 2006.</ref> She was not included among the selectable fighters in the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] and [[Sega Genesis]] version of ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'' due to memory constraints, though she appeared as a glitch character in the SNES version of ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]''.  Sheeva's blood was green in ''MK3'' through ''[[Mortal Kombat Trilogy]]'' (although if this was done simply because she was a Shokan, it made little sense, seeing as both Goro and Kintaro had red blood in previous games). She was the first character to have this particular blood color (not counting the censored Japanese version of ''[[Mortal Kombat II]]'', in which all characters had green blood). Her blood color was changed to red in ''Armageddon''.\n\nUntil the release of ''MK: Armageddon'', Sheeva had not appeared as a playable character since ''MK Trilogy'', nor did she have had any substantial cameos; only her corpse was found in the Netherealm in ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deception]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Konquest mode and is seen running through the graveyard in the game's Krypt, in which almost all ''MK'' characters had cameos. Her fate after ''MK Trilogy'' was revealed in the text from ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Konquest mode. In ''Armageddon'''s arcade mode, Sheeva sometimes appeared as a sub-boss before the final fight with Blaze. She is the only Shokan character that can perform aerial combos, and the only Shokan character that can be thrown by normal characters in the game. While she has Goro's offensive moves, she is female so that she would be smaller in size and therefore the same height as the other fighters.\n\n===In other media===\nSheeva appears in ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]],'' played by [[Marjean Holden]]. The [[shooting script]] included a lengthy fight scene with [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]] that was omitted during filming; instead, she was simply crushed by a falling cage in Kahn's throne room. Her only action sequence was a brief quarrel with Motaro, though the film did acknowledge that she was once Sindel's personal protector. In a 2001 interview with fansite Total Mortal Kombat, Holden expressed her displeasure at the filmmakers' treatment of her character. In the [[shooting script]] and novelization, Sheeva met her demise in an extensive fight scene with newly mortal Raiden, but the scene was never filmed and her screen time was scant in the finished print, with Raiden instead fighting two Raptors and Sheeva's death simply coming from a falling cage. \"Here was a character, that was one of the most popular [in] the video game...and they killed her without even so much as a fight! Something I was not happy about at all. That was one of the reasons I wanted to do the role, was for the sheer fact that there were really great fights in the movie for this character, and they all got cut out.\"<ref name=\"tmk\">[http://www.totalmortalkombat.com/cast/interviews/index.php?action=interview&interview_id=2 Interview with: Marjean Holden] - Total Mortal Kombat, 2/4/01</ref>\n\nSheeva has a small role in the animated series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'', in which she harbored a long-standing animosity toward Raiden. She was voiced by [[Dawnn Lewis]].\n\nIn the 2015 ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]'' prequel comic miniseries produced by [[DC Comics]], Sheeva is crowned by Kintaro as the current leader of the Shokan in a peaceful treaty with Kotal Kahn, following the death of previous rule King Gorbak. Sheeva mourned Kintaro's death when a possessed [[Sonya Blade]] killed him in battle.\n\n==Reception==\nReception of the character has been mixed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheevafanclub.wordpress.com/|title=Sheeva Fan Club|website=Sheeva Fan Club|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref> ''SuperGamePower'' gave her their anti-awards for the ugliest female character of both 1996 and 1997.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1997|title=Os melhores do videogame|url=|journal=SuperGamePower|volume=38|pages=15|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=May 1998|title=II Oscar do videogame|url=|journal=SuperGamePowe|volume=50|pages=11|via=}}</ref> In 2011, [[Wirtualna Polska]] featured her among the top ten villainesses in gaming, as \"an attraction for connoisseurs of unusual beauty and even more unusual quantities of the various parts of the body.\"<ref>[http://gry.wp.pl/galeria/10-najseksowniejszych-negatywnych-bohaterek,179679/10.html Sheeva \u2013 Mortal Kombat - 10 najseksowniejszych negatywnych bohaterek - Imperium gier - WP.PL] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321150440/http://gry.wp.pl/galeria/10-najseksowniejszych-negatywnych-bohaterek,179679/10.html |date=2012-03-21 }} {{in lang|pl}}</ref> In 2012, [[UGO.com]] ranked her as the 28th top ''Mortal Kombat'' character.<ref>{{cite web |author=UGO Team |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters-sheeva |title=Sheeva - Top 50 Mortal Kombat Characters |publisher=UGO.com |date=2012-02-28 |accessdate=2012-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316074322/http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters-sheeva |archivedate=2013-03-16 }}</ref> Sheeva ranked 36th on a 2013 fan poll hosted by Dorkly that rated the entire series roster. Den of Geek ranked Sheeva 34th in their 2015 rating of the franchises 64 characters. However, ''[[Game Informer]]'' listed her as one of the characters they did not want for ''MK2011'', stating that \"despite a somewhat cool ground-pound move, she was an addition to the series that never really served a purpose or did anything particularly noteworthy.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ulrich |first=Tyler |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2010/06/21/who-we-want-and-dont-want-in-the-new-mortal-kombat.aspx?PostPageIndex=2&PageIndex=6 |title=Who We Want (And Don\u2019t Want) In The New Mortal Kombat - Features |publisher=www.GameInformer.com |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> GamePlayBook ranked Sheeva fifth on their top 10 worst characters in the series. She was ranked as seventh goofiest ''Mortal Kombat'' character by [[Topless Robot]] in 2011.<ref name=goofy>{{cite web|url=http://www.toplessrobot.com/2011/04/8_mortal_kombat_characters_that_are_goofy_even_by.php |title=8 Mortal Kombat Characters That Are Goofy Even by Mortal Kombat Standards |publisher=Topless Robot |date=2011-04-14 |accessdate=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n\nSheeva was featured in several lists of the best, and sometimes worst, finishing moves in the ''Mortal Kombat'' series by various publications. In 1996, her \"Skin Rip\" move received the most votes for favorite ''Mortal Kombat 3'' finishing move from ''[[GamePro]]'' readers.<ref>{{cite journal|last= |first= |title=Reader Report|journal=[[GamePro]]|issue=91|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=April 1996|page=13}}</ref> In 2010, [[IGN]] ranked her \"Manly Forearms\" from ''MK3'' as the third best Fatality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ps3.ign.com/articles/113/1137436p1.html |title=IGN's Unofficial Top 10 List of the Best Mortal Kombat Fatalities - PS3 Feature at IGN |publisher=Uk.ps3.ign.com |date=2010-11-30 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>  In 2011, she placed third on the lists of both the best (\"Skin Rip\" in ''MK3'') and the worst (\"Jackhammer\" in ''MK3'') Fatalities by GameRant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/top-10-best-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-75792/all/1/ |title=Top 10 Best Mortal Kombat Fatalities |publisher=Game Rant |date= |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/worst-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-79624/all/1/ |title=Top Ten Worst 'Mortal Kombat' Fatalities |publisher=Game Rant |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref> In 2012, [[GameFront]] ranked her \"Stripped Down\" Fatality from ''[[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|Mortal Kombat 2011]]'' as the third best in the series,<ref>{{cite web|author=Andy Gold |url=http://www.gamefront.com/mortal-kombats-10-best-fatalities/ |title=Mortal Kombat\u2019s 10 Best Fatalities |publisher=GameFront |date=2011-04-20 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref> while her other Fatality was also ranked as the ninth best in this game by ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nathan Spicer |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/04/best-fatalities-from-mortal-kombat-1-and-9.html |title=The 17 Best Fatalities from Mortal Kombat 1 & 9 :: Blogs :: List of the Day :: Paste |publisher=Pastemagazine.com |date=2011-04-23 |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Mortal Kombat series}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by John Tobias]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Female characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional bodyguards in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional hybrid life forms]]\n[[Category:Mortal Kombat characters]]\n[[Category:Video game antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in film]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in literature]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in television]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 1995]]\n\n[[fr:Sheeva]]\n[[pt:Sheeva]]\n", "name_user": "117.198.226.164", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheeva"}
